<font size='20'><font face='$76HandwrittenNeat_Font'>Last chronicle of Sgt. Ning, Hellcat Company -- or what's left of it, anyway.    We've spent a long time in the Pitt. The wars among its occupants have been incessant, but all that is finally drawing to a close. Not much left in the way of resistance, anymore. The Fanatics own damn near everything. Only the Union remains... Until this monolith falls apart and it starts all over again.    We made the right choice becoming mercenaries, I still believe that. Fought on every which side and made a killing doing it. We came out on top, and now we should get the hell out before the Fanatics turn on us, too.    Some of the others may have doubts, given the casualties we've sustained, and I get that. Has to be that half of us are gone now, from when I started. Maybe more, hard to keep count. But that's behind us now. I have no interest in sticking around to find out what "peace time" means for these raiders. I'm moving on to greener pastures.    This world needs its killers, or its defenders, or whatever you'll pay me to be. Have to be other towns out there just as fucked as we were by the war and the bombs and everything that goes with it. I hear Kit's taking some of the others and heading south, but that sounds weak... Appalachia is soft, no bombs there, no challenge.    No, I'll go elsewhere. See what trouble I can get into. Gets my blood pumping just thinking about it.

31148 chews through these cheap plastic barrels like a kid at a candy store. This is going to become a huge problem when you consider that failed batches like 31148-042 react exponentially more violent than successful batches. If one of these barrels leaks a failed batch and a reaction is triggered, you are talking about shutting down an entire city block for weeks to clean up the fallout. Surely an outcome like that is worth avoiding by just paying for the dam metal barrels? A concerned employee

Abraxodyne Chemical Complex, PGH

REVISION TO WASTE STORAGE POLICY ---------------------

Due to financial circumstances out of our control, metal waste barrels will be unavailable to us going forward. Plastic barrels will be used in the meantime. In the event of corrosive wastes damaging the integrity of the container, efforts should be taken to reseal the container instead of retrieving a new one. Application of adhesive tape and Wonderglue is the current recommended solution. Questions or concerns about the new barrels can be left with Sydney, and she will make sure they get to my desk. Edgar Clemmon

<font size='17'>Orders say we can't arm the Ressies, but I say the hell with that.    Nobody knows what you're going to face out there, so I'll be damned if I let you do it with nothing but a winning smile and a good attitude. I've snuck a pistol in with the rest of your supplies. Not like the weapons are doing any good sitting in storage here, anyway.    Good luck. We're all going to need it.

FULL: Plan: Cappy and Bottle Couple Signs

DESC: Del     For the last time stop feeding my brother those chems! You're a doctor not a dealer, he doesn't need a fix, he needs help! I'm serious.    Pat

<font face='$HandwrittenFont'>Pat's been trying to convince me that the medicine Del gives me isn't good for me. She says stuff's bad for me and that I need a different outlet. Guess I could give it a try? I found an old book a while back, full of poems and stuff. I like reading them, maybe I'll try writing my own?  [pagebreak]  Long, cold, desolate  the winding road we travel  how long has it been?  [pagebreak]  Taking the prescription Del gives me really helps me write this stuff. I don't think I want to show anyone yet. Better not tell Pat either, she's got enough to worry about with the terminal breaking and records being lost.   [pagebreak]   Making you feel so small  You become a child once more  Daddy-O  The smaller you are  the higher you get  the higher you get  the more lonely you are  But I found comfort in my solitude  In my solitude  I found company in my monsters  And suddenly  my monsters started dancing  [pagebreak]  I might have gone too far this time. Pat is absolutely furious. I should... ergh hang on imma be sick again ...  [pagebreak]  Bump. bump. Bump.  The feeling in my chest  A slow rhythm beats  Wont let me rest.  Bump, bump, bump.  The cart's broken wheel  Do you hear it?  Wont let me heal.  Bumpbumpbump  Can feel my heart rate slowing  Mustn't let it go down.  The fury keeps me going  [pagebreak]  I'm sick of raiders constantly disturbing our peace. We're out here trying to bring some joy and light to the wastelands and we keep attracting selfish bastards that kill our families and take our goods. Poor Chloe got a real battering. I had to update her program to get her back up and running, back to her usual self popping all the baloons.  [pagebreak]  A Wasteland take on a Rossetti classic.  It is over. what is over?  This old world now over truly  The glory days my parents yearned for;  Now the rad dust gathers newly  While our wagons travel duly  It is finished. What is finished?  We are finished, known or unknown  Lives are finished; time diminished;  Abandoned fields are left unsown  In their place mutated crops grown  It suffices. What suffices?  All suffices reckoned rightly:  We shall roam where roads entice us,  This new world's done naught but spite me  And though this Ash Heap is unsightly,  And our wagon waiting idly,  We carry on whatever the price is  [pagebreak]  I saw something crazy big up on the hill behind the camp. I wanted to check it out, make sure we were safe here but Pat doesn't believe me. Del's thinking about increasing my perscription. I swear I'm not crazy! Just need a way to prove it...  </font>

June 8th  Finally. Away from the Blood Eagles. Managed to snag some Addictol, maybe it'll be enough to stave off the cravings. I'm never going back. Those guys, the things they do... It's crazy. Just gotta keep my head low and watch out for patrols. Just need something to help me keep going.  [pagebreak]  July 10th  Got a tip that there's a rare ore in the Ash Heap called "Ultracite." There's always someone looking for rare stuff like that who'll pay good caps for it. If I can get my hands on some, maybe I can trade it for enough supplies and finally get out of here. See the world! ... what's left of it.  [pagebreak]  July 24th  Happy birthday to me! Found some info on the old mine shafts in the Ash Heap. Gotta be some of that ore in one of them! Found an old holotape too. Some crazy story about some monster in the mines. Gotta be something they made up to scare off the locals.  [pagebreak]  August 15th  Swiped some gear from an old Responders place. Should be able to get to the mines in the Ash Heap safely now. Just missed a Blood Eagle patrol. Guy looked pissed. Better cover my tracks.   [pagebreak]  September 3rd  Found a place to hold up in old Lewisburg. Looks like there's a few old mines nearby. If I can get past the locals I might be able to get this ore and get the heck outta here.  [pagebreak]  September 7th  Nothin' around that mine on the hill. Movin' on. There's another one a little ways away. Bumped into some Raiders in an old storehouse. Shot first, asked questions later. Looks like they weren't Blood Eagles. Feel sorry for 'em but couldn't take any risks. Was gunna bury the bodies but Mole Miners were on patrol. Going to have to leave them there.  [pagebreak]  September 10th  Now is my chance. Heading to the mine. Gotta travel light. I'll hide a few things here and come back once I'm done. No point draggin' all my stuff with me.

<font size='18'>Dear Gunther,   Here is a list of things that are safer than this abomination you call a show.   1. A room full of cultists!  2. A nuclear blast!!  3. Sleeping next to an irradiated barrel!!!  4. A pack of hungry dogs!!!!  5. Anything else other than this!!!!!</font>

<font face='$HandwrittenFont' size='15'>  To the psycho running the "show".    Your "Wild West Showdown" got me shot, TWICE!!!   When I was cowering in the saloon screaming for you to stop the damn show, you just started announcing "Oh no the Sheriff is coming!", then that thing started launching bombs! BOMBS!!! What's the matter with you?!    I barely made it out there alive! I even lost my teddy bear in your hell hole! And what did you have to say after? "Welcome to the wild west", this is a god damn death trap you psycho!    Me and mine are never coming back here, and trust me, you'll get what's coming to you some day!

[2095/06/27]  Poppa is mad with me again... I don't even know what I did wrong now! I don't think   I did anything wrong... I think for him I do everything wrong because Mom didn't make it when I joined this world... I wonder what Mom was like... I wonder if Poppa would have been kinder to me if we all would have been together... Or if she would have protected me? Or if she would have been on his side? I wonder if I am anything like her? I think Poppa is just sad... sad to have lost her... he blames me  every day... but I didn't get a choice... if I did I would have gone instead...    [pagebreak]   [2100/01/03]  Today I made Poppa happy. He joined Mom today. I served him his last suppa. He didn't even finish it. Had 5 mouths full of it then just drifted off... I told him I loved him and that I hope he will be happy together with Mom. It won't make too much of a difference to me... I was already lonely... maybe now I can go and find myself my own family?     [pagebreak]  [2100/07/18]  Maybe being alone is a little tougher than I thought it would be but I won't let this drag me down! I've been going out scavenging in the areas Poppa told me not to - see what I can find beyond our little camp. I found all sorts of cool stuff like some more comics from the before times! Oh how I wish I was born then...     [pagebreak]   [2101/02/13]  I don't know what's happening to me! All my hair has been slowly falling out and I've been getting rashes on my skin. I've not been feeling quite right either... Maybe I'm being punished! I think I'm dying. I came across some other people the other day and they started throwing things at me and shouting "You ugly Ghoul!". So even if I'm not dying, who will fall in love with me looking like... this?!  [pagebreak]   [2104/10/10]  Oh today is the happiest day of my life! I found this traveling Carnival setting up near Lewisburg and they took me in! I'm finally going to travel the country and hopefully I'll find a spot that is close to what the world used to be before the bombs dropped. I've read sooo much about the world before the war! It looked so  nice. Just imagine being able to go for a walk and not having to kill Radroaches or be chased by a Deathclaw! Oh what I would give to have lived then - have my own little family,  husband and 2 beautiful children. I would be cooking them the best food in our fabulous bright kitchen - pie on the windowsill filling the house with a sweet smell. I would have never turned into this thing either... kept my beautiful hair... maybe I can still find something like this now... maybe with this Carnival... they seem very accepting and I'm not the only Ghoul around!    [pagebreak]    [2104/10/12]  Pat assigned me to one of the stalls today - selling goods to visitors! Oh I'm so excited! I'll do my very best to not disappoint Pat! Her brother Pete is also very nice - bit strange at times - but oh my he is so cute! He tells the best stories! I hope to get to know him better soon. Del can be a little grumpy but I just have to infect him with my positivity! I'm pretty sure he is a good guy underneath his hard shell. And Gunther! Oh I love him already! So good to get to know another Ghoul. He explained me all about our condition and it made me feel less bad about my appearance and accepting myself for who I am. He even found me an old wig and gave it to me. It's sooo pretty! Seeing another human alive and well after turning into a ghoul gives me hope. I'm so excited to become part of their family - finally I have something to look forward to in my future.

[2055/06/24]  Still think about Tabitha from time to time, but definitely wanna forget those assholes at the orphanage. Don't regret it though, not right treating a lady like that, especially Tabitha.     Thought he could get away with saying that shit in front of me, what was he thinking? Back's got a few kinks from roughing it last night, gonna have to find some permanent digs soon now I can't go back. Eight years...     Don't regret it though, punk got what he deserved.    [pagebreak]  [2056/07/05]  Nuka-World, still can't believe they hired a bum like me. A travelling western show... never did imagine my cowboy impressions would score a gig like this. I guess my old man getting me into binging old westerns weren't a waste of time after all. Still miss the old man and mom every time I watch them old films.    So this is a new chapter, good riddance to the orphanage and about time I left Boston. Time to see the rest of this fine ass country, and one day those dusty Texan dunes.    Looking forward to teaching the kiddos how to be real little cowboys and cowgirls, like my old man showed me. Lord knows with all the fuss over the energy crisis, we need a break from all the doom and gloom.    [pagebreak]  [2077/10/24]  As I sit here waiting for the rumbling to stop, it's stupid but all I can think about is that I never got to go to Texas, and I wonder if there's even a Texas left to visit.    So the commies actually did it... Saw the bombs from a distance, rushed into sewers to keep safe along with some other folk. In all the commotion most scattered, no idea if they're safe and if there's a world above worth going back to. Got little Pat and Pete with me to worry about. I'm hoping their folks are hunkering down because last thing I'd want is for these kids to end up as orphans like me. Will have to go out and look for them soon I guess.    Worst fucking morning show I ever ran...    [pagebreak]  [2092/09/02]  Still regret going out after the bombs dropped. I thought losing my hair was bad enough, but my skin started to rot, then my damn nose fell off! Yet death never came by some miracle or curse. Worse yet been seeing others like me, crazed damn zombies, ghouls people call them. I've even had to put some of those poor mindless creatures down. Every time I do, I add a notch to my piece, wondering when I'll finally lose it and become a notch for someone else... I often wonder if Muriel and Randall would have gone that way if their time was not cut short.    The kids help keep my mind off it though, and we've been focusing on altering the attractions and keeping the fair going. Pete's become a wiz at mechanics like his old man, been helping me tweak and set up the wild west showdown attraction. He struggles sometimes with the lifestyle in this new world, and I can't blame him. So Del has been keeping an eye on him for us and prescribing him chems to help him cope.    As for Pat, real determined that one, like her mom. She had to grow up real fast due to what happened to her folks. Heck, after the camp got raided some time back, morale was real low, she was the only thing that kept us going, even when some quit. I think it's because the carnival is all she's ever known, and she keeps it going in memory of her folks. Got her to jot down her thoughts in a journal a bit back so she could process it all, seems to be doing the trick, lord knows it helps me.    Carnival life ain't perfect these days but I'll keep them safe, I owe Muriel and Randall that much. Afterall, love them kids like they're my own, and they never treated me any different, even after I lost my sniffer.    [pagebreak]  [2098/06/17]  This kid is gonna be the end of me. Looks like he took a few too many chems and nearly overdosed. Pat came pounding on my trailer last night when she found him zonked out. Del fixed him back up, but I'll have to have a word with him about those prescriptions in the morning. Don't think the boy wants to end it, probably just messed up the dose. He needs to learn his limits I guess, because if this wild wasteland won't get him, the chems might.    Though looking at his work, the results help you overlook the character flaw. The attractions are in tip top shape and we've even re-programmed the bots we found to do all sorts of antics. Boy's a genius with a bad habit, and I don't mean the poetry. Depression is a hard thing to kick, took me a spell to kick mine before Nuka- World. We'll just have to find him something or someone to change his tune.    [pagebreak]  [2104/10/15]  Came across many folk like myself over the years, but none who were born after the bombs dropped. Betty is her name, and she was pretty worn down when we met her, needed her affliction explained and told it's not a curse. Being a ghoul for nearly 30 years I can say despite the rough skin and looks, I'm not feeling so bad for someone in their 60's and the rads don't bother me no more. She's become a fine addition to the family, and we've been helping her adjust. Got her one of the old show wigs and we gave her a job at the fair. It's also looking like she might have a thing for my Pete. Lucky kid, maybe she'll be the one to help him kick his old habits.    We've been settling just outside Lewisburg for a spell, the Ash Heap people are calling it. Not my first choice of a spot, but we are revisiting old show tour stops. Been setting up the attractions for the past few days, all good and running except the Nuka-Launcher. Pete's having some issues with it for some time now. Starting to think he's skipping work and getting hopped up on chems again. Hoping Betty will keep an eye on him for us and help change his tune.

[2083/02/07] Dear Diary... Is that how you start a diary? I don't know how you do this sorta thing...
Gunther said it would be good for me... to get some feelings down... to "process the grief" he said...
I don't even know how to process?... how do you process something that you can't hold?
Anyway... he's the adult. I trust him to know what he's talking about... although am I the adult now too?
I thought we were so lucky that Mom, Pops, Pete and me all survived the bombs. But now it's just Pete and me. I'm responsible for him now... and for the Carnival? Gunther is wrong, this isn't helping at all! I just feel angrier now! Bye!!! [pagebreak] [2091/09/17] It's been a minute since mom and pops passed. I still miss them every day. But at least I got Pete!
He's a full grown adult now... setting up all the attractions and repairing all sorts. He worries me though - he's never quite gotten over the fact mom and pops are gone.
He is such a sweet soul... I don't think this new world is for him, but he'll battle through! I'm sure! Just gotta make sure I'm there for him...
We've been traveling around much keeping the Carnival going. Making some caps here and there. We've lost so many along the way. It's not always easy to keep strong. Sometimes I don't see the reason to keep going with it all but then I remember Mom and Pops and I continue for them. [pagebreak] [2094/07/18] I swear I'm going to kill that idiot Del. I found Pete in a ditch today, absolutely pumped on Daddy-O again. He's gonna die one day if Del keeps giving him these Chems. He is wrong. They absolutely do not help him...
I question myself as to why we keep letting him be part of the Carnival... I'll have a chat with Gunther later to get his opinion on it.
I know Pete is not a child anymore but he sure doesn't act like a grown up. I don't know how I'll ever be able to trust him to look after himself. I need to keep him safe. He is the last of my family... [pagebreak] [2104/10/05] We've been attacked again and lost a few of our group... they all scattered into different directions trying to get away. I'm not sure they all made it but I sure hope they will all make their way back to us.
We're just gonna keep setting up around the Ash Heap. Hoping they'll see our attractions and come join us again. It's not that easy getting it all set up with the missing workforce, but we've managed before and we'll manage again! And who knows... maybe we'll have a few new travelers join us.

July 15 2077 Honestly if Claire and Derek leave their food out one more time I'll collect all their dirty rubbish and scatter it all over their office desks. This is a medical facility and hygiene should be of utmost importance!
But that's not even the worst - the rides and attractions here are so poorly engineered we keep having accidents and injuries. There is not a day that goes past where I don't have a crying kid sat in the infirmary with a laceration. We already had 2 fatalities too, and I guarantee it won't take long for a third.
But nobody in my department seems to care that much about it so I have left a holotape for Bradberton directly. Let's see what he's got to say...
The only thing keeping me sane at the moment is my small allotment, at least there I can take simple actions if something is growing out of control. [pagebreak] July 18 2077 So Bradberton never got back to me directly but Nuka-World has offered me a new exciting role for their new Nuka-World on Tour.
I would have to leave my allotment behind and travel the country but I would be in charge of all things health and safety - wouldn't that be something?
I could finally tell my parents I've made it to a high-ranking position. The pay wouldn't be the best but they don't need to know that. [pagebreak] August 01 2077 I'm now the Physician in charge of Nuka-World on Tour! Although my parents were still not very impressed with it... said that being in charge of a tent in a theme park wasn't a real medical profession.
Maybe I should have just ignored them and pursued what truly makes me happy, but I guess it's a little too late now.
I'll be setting off tomorrow and already got to meet some of the people who will be traveling with me. Randall and Muriel are the couple in charge of the main Carnival and they seem alright. Hopefully we won't be dealing with as many injuries as Nuka-World with me in charge of Health and Safety. [pagebreak] February 03 2083 The world is a dreadful place... just death and destruction. Guess this Carnival needs me more than ever now with the world being such a dangerous place, they're lucky they've got a professional medic in their group.
Randall and Muriel didn't make it. I pity their kids, but there wasn't much I could do for their parents.
My old allotment sounds like heaven now... [pagebreak] July 19 2094 What a lost soul Pete is. He can't cope without my prescriptions. Pat doesn't understand that it is me who is keeping her brother alive. Keeps sending me threats but I won't listen.
That boy needs his meds or he will be a threat not only to himself but also others. Pat should really leave the medical stuff to me. I'm the doctor around here after all and she has no idea how it all works.

DESC: <font face='$HandwrittenFont'>  September 11th  I don't like being so close to my old camp. One of them spots me I'm dead... fuckers didn't even know they were sat next to a gold mine. The mole miners should keep em busy for now.    September 12th  Damn it!! I wasted the whole day trying to mine that ore. My bullets didn't even leave a mark. I'll find a pickaxe or something with more WHACK tomorrow.    September 13th  The mine's really shaking. I wonder if it has anything to do with the ore reacting strange. I swear there's more ore here than yesterday.    September 14th  Fuck! My pickaxe slipped, I managed to clean the wound. The pain was unbearable. I found some Psycho in that Chem box. One won't hurt, it's just for the pain then I'm done with it.    September 15th  The ground won't stop shaking, shit feels like the whole damn mine is gonna collapse. Dunno if I'm losing my mind, or what, but I swear there's gotta be something down there.     September 16th  Out of my meds, there's nothing left to take the edge off. This place is getting to me, but this crystal? ULTRACITE? That pays its weight in caps. Gonna crack open a big one today, sell it to the next caravan that comes through, maybe get some gear to make this hell more bearable...

Hey 'Genie.    I know it's been a while since my last note. Gonna keep it short, don't wanna be all sappy.     I get why you left, we all do. I know we disagree on things, especially this. We just wanted to say that if you ever wanted to come by, you're always welcome to. Things ain't the same.   [pagebreak]  We're all keepin on', finally fixed that faulty bulb that used to piss you off. Jaye found an old guitar in a house the other week, shame she can't tune the thing for shit. I'm making sure your bed doesn't get too dusty.     Just in case.    From Kev, and the rest of us.

<font size='20' color='#040078'>Deb,    Remember how Kenny had a job at the Garrahan mine just down the road? Turns out they had some supplies locked away. The ground there may be unstable, but anything is worth the risk with our stash running low. Going to check the place out.    Give my love to Carver,  Greg  </font>

<font size='20' color='#040078'>  To my family,    My leg's been crushed real bad, and the heat in here is... well, it's killing me. Literally, I'm sure. Let this serve as my last will and testament.    Deb. Whatever you've got going on between you and your Van Lowe friend... I get it. Actually, I don't get it, but I get that I don't get it. And that's all right. I hope both you and her can live a happier life than the one I tried making for us. I'm sorry I didn't try harder. Truly. Please keep Carver safe in whatever is left of this world.    Carver, my boy, know that I loved you. Know that I wouldn't leave you behind if it were my choice. I've made many foolish mistakes, but that's a part of life. Wish I could be there to help you learn from yours.    I've got my lucky lighter on me. I want you to have it.     It's worth a pretty penny, so sell it if you need to. But more than anything, I want you to have SOMETHING from me.    If anyone stumbles upon this, my name is Gregory Timmerman. I'm from Lewisburg. My family is Deborah Timmerman (maiden name Clark), and Carver Timmerman. I beg of you to find it in your heart to bring this to them.    Greg  </font>

<font face='$HandwrittenFont' size='18'>Oh my shepherd. Such blessings you have cast upon us.    Grant us your strength once more, for we have found a beast worthy of being sacrificed in your holy name.     It's blood is ancient, holding secrets of long ago.    The creature has traveled south and we have trudged through the night in pursuit of the hunt, though our endeavors thus far have proved unfruitful.  [pagebreak]  The monster is strong and savage, snapping in two those that dare step near its vicious jaws.    It appears to have taken up residency near a vast bog, and we too have created shelter here whilst we prepare defenses and plans to vanquish it.     When the time is right, blood will spill and it shall offer your divine sight visions of ages past.

Stuff I need:  A big box of different spices -- cumin, onion powder, etc...  A box of Pork n' Beans cans.  A box of dehydrated radishes.  A box of dried beans - pinto, if possible.  A box of dried chilies - guajillo or ancho, but I can make do with whatever.      Stuff I can get on my own:  Chicken, tatos, corn, salt and pepper...

DESC: <font size='15'>Vin's got a sick sense of humor making me babysit and pull maid duty.    Too many freeloaders leaving junk behind in the bunks. Not enough high rollers buying drinks. Still got some of the strong stuff left too, but only good for lunkheads that can hold their liquor. At least I get to take out my frustrations on the local wildlife when they come looking for hamburger.    Still can't believe I lost my best shirt fishing caps out the crapper, all because that chica is such a klutz. Good kid, but she's obviously been coddled her whole life. She's gonna need to toughen up though before something puts her in the ground.    Actually, I guess Vin put me here to prevent just that...

1. Write a "Get RICH Quick" guide 2. Find a sucker...

Come on! Don't get mad. Get some caps! Pass it on.

Sorry fellas, they got me good.  Stupid cavern used to be an easy spot to rest the night and score some long-forgotten goods, but... those big green guys came outta no where. Managed to outrun em, but... well you're probably looking at me, right?    Biggest joke of all is that I didn't score any loot. Just some whacko's poetry reading.   Sad that this is the last thing I'm gonna hear, but... Yeah, they got me good.

<font face='$HandwrittenFont' size='18'>Holy Mothman, once again you have granted us such benevolent opportunities.    Whilst tracking the creature, Elder Adelaide stumbled upon a mindless merchant traveling the roads and crafted a wise, guileful scheme. She posed as a trader and organized a deal for later that week.    We spent days crafting an ambush.  When the time came, we overpowered the fool and took his supplies, ammunition and pack animal... though the coward knew better than to fight back.   [pagebreak]  Some explosive contraptions were also among the plunder. They appear crude but will be effective none the less. Was this another gift from you, oh divine one?  This thundering wrath could aid us in raining hellfire on our enemy.    We pray for your continued guidance. Soon, you will bear witness to a worthy offering and your merciful kindness will be rewarded.

<font size='20' color='#040078'>Investigation complete.    They used to breed them way, way back. First for racing, then for fighting. Kept going after the bombs. That doesn't explain their size, though.    Could have something to do with that place, and what's near by. At this point, impossible to tell.    They're reproducing out in the wild, but most litters don't produce healthy enough pups to survive. The one's that do, though, grow up... fast. Immediately hostile, even young-- so don't even consider it.    Color variations are limited, especially local specimen. Dark black hair is most common, appearing almost blue in certain light. None were "Z?B2Y" like you suggested.    Payment has been received. This concludes our business.  </font>

<font face='$HandwrittenFont'><font size='16'>Hey newcomers,    Welcome to Appalachia. Hell of a place, isn't it? There's a lot of danger and a lot of excitement waiting for you.    I got some help when I first stepped into this big, beautiful, irradiated world... I figure you deserve the same. So in that spirit, I built a little box for gift giving. A place for the haves to leave something for the have nots. If you see something you want, take it. If not, well... you'll survive.    Good luck out there.    Signed,  Your Friendly Neighborhood Wastelander

Scenario Generated: The Good Doctor You give the patient acetaminophen, hoping it will treat him. Unlike the antibiotic supply, there's an unusual abundance of it in the clinic. He happily takes the pill and agrees to continue with it until his symptoms alleviate. As the week progresses, you notice that his condition only worsens. He grows paler and paler and loses his appetite. Is it possible you made the wrong diagnosis? Or maybe it was the wrong treatment? No, maybe it just needs more time. You continue to give him acetaminophen. One day, the patient ceases to enter the clinic. You wait around all day and even stay an extra half hour after you usually close. He doesn't show. The next day, you see a few other settlers standing around a fresh grave. You may continue in your endeavors as a doctor, but you've certainly failed your own patient.

Biff Bronson's Wacky Wasteland Adventures! (TM)

PLAY-THROUGH RESULTS ---------------------

Scenario Generated: Sharing is Caring "This isn't worth it," you say out loud. With that, you turn around to leave. With your back turned, the thief decides to take her chance. She dashes over to you, and before you can turn around, she forcefully jabs a knife into your back. You try to push her away, but the pain overwhelms you. You fall to the ground and ask her "Why?" She replies that she couldn't trust that you wouldn't come back for her. You fall to the ground as your vision slowly fades to black. Maybe you shouldn't just turn your back on someone like that. But it's too late to learn that lesson now.

Biff Bronson's Wacky Wasteland Adventures! (TM)

PLAY-THROUGH RESULTS ---------------------

Scenario Generated: Sharing is Caring You shoot at the thief, aiming a fatal shot. The bullet goes straight past her head, not even grazing her. You pull the trigger again, only to reveal an empty chamber. The thief hears the empty click and draws her knife. She pursues you, now fearless in her attempts. You try to flee, but she's much faster. She catches up to you and tackles you to the ground. Before you can react, she shoves the knife straight into your heart. You took the risk, and it blew up in your face. "We could've talked this out," she says breathlessly, as your vision slowly fades to black.

Biff Bronson's Wacky Wasteland Adventures! (TM)

PLAY-THROUGH RESULTS ---------------------

Scenario Generated: Sharing is Caring You don't care what her reasoning is. You just want your things back. You attempt to push past the thief to brute force reclaiming your belongings. The thief pushes you back shouting, "You can't just take it all from me!" You ignore her, thinking her to be harmless, and continue gathering your things. You have your back turned to her when you feel a sharp, intense pain. Your eyes widen as you feel the knife in your back. You fall to your knees as you turn around and see the thief standing behind you. She looks almost surprised by what she did. "I told you to stop," she says quietly. "I warned you." You fall to the ground and bleed out. All of this over some rations that could have been replaced.

Biff Bronson's Wacky Wasteland Adventures! (TM)

PLAY-THROUGH RESULTS ---------------------

Scenario Generated: Atomic Adam You hold up the flower, telling Adam that it isn't too late to change his ways and that maybe you can still resolve this peacefully. Adam laughs and lifts his giant foot. Your eyes widen and the flower cartoonishly flops over as the massive shadow of Adam's foot looms over you. You scream as he stomps on the ground, crushing you to a pulp. You die instantly.

Biff Bronson's Wacky Wasteland Adventures! (TM)

PLAY-THROUGH RESULTS ---------------------

Scenario Generated: Meltdown You get to work and try to fix the reactor to the best of your abilities. Despite your best efforts, it looks like you made a crucial mistake: You turned the knob the wrong way. You hardly have time to scream as the reactor has a total meltdown, killing you instantly. Nevertheless, your fate was the least painful. The vault won't be remotely habitable for hundreds of years, and its denizens will be left to perish in the Wasteland.

Biff Bronson's Wacky Wasteland Adventures! (TM)

PLAY-THROUGH RESULTS ---------------------

Scenario Generated: The Good Doctor You explain to the man with a complete lack of remorse that to try any kind of treatment right now would just worsen his pain and provide no benefit whatsoever. His face falls as the last shred of hope he held vainly onto disappears. He quietly asks you what he should do. You tell him to meet you outside behind the clinic. The man follows you outside and you silently draw a pistol from your belt. With his back to you, you pull the trigger. You look down at his corpse. An utterly pointless death. If you were willing to spend half an hour and use your supplies, this wouldn't have happened. In the future if you fall sick, maybe you'll survive, but at what cost? You lived, I guess. But man, you're a horrible human being.

Biff Bronson's Wacky Wasteland Adventures! (TM)

PLAY-THROUGH RESULTS ---------------------

Scenario Generated: Meltdown You chewed your gum adequately, to the point where it can act as a temporary adhesive. You spot an incriminating tiny hole in the reactor's shell that might be causing the issue. You take the gum out of your mouth and use it to plug the hole. Suddenly, the emergency alert system shuts off. Your eyes widen in shock. Even YOU are flummoxed that it actually worked. Somehow, you saved the day.

Biff Bronson's Wacky Wasteland Adventures! (TM)

PLAY-THROUGH RESULTS ---------------------

Scenario Generated: Meltdown At a loss as to an actual solution, you throw yourself into the reactor hoping that sacrificing yourself to the radiation gods will spare the whole vault. Unfortunately, your rationale was nonsensical and not exactly useful. You perish instantly, and the reactor has a fullblown meltdown. If anything, the meltdown was accelerated by your intervention. The vault becomes an inhospitable hellhole where no human will be able to venture for centuries to come. All thanks to you.

Biff Bronson's Wacky Wasteland Adventures! (TM)

Scenario Generated: Meltdown You get to work and fix the reactor to the best of your abilities. It seems your experienced judgement was correct, and the reactor sputters back to life! The emergency alert system powers down. You sigh in relief as cheers of triumph erupt from the vault's upper levels. You've saved the day after all! For the rest of your days in the vault, you've earned the reputation of a hero. But at the end of the day, you were just doing your job.

Biff Bronson's Wacky Wasteland Adventures! (TM)

Scenario Generated: Sharing is Caring You shoot out into the bushes without thinking. You hear a cry of pain and a massive thump as a body falls to the ground. You run out and see a total stranger dead and bleeding out on the dirt. You have no idea who they are, but they aren't carrying any of your things. This probably wasn't the thief. Out of pure mortification, you retreat back into your tattered tent and make the resolution to just move your base camp and start over. Maybe you don't need all of those rations. You just need to get far, far away from here, until you can bury this memory deep in the vault.

Biff Bronson's Wacky Wasteland Adventures! (TM)

PLAY-THROUGH RESULTS ---------------------

Scenario Generated: The Good Doctor So maybe the life of a settlement doctor is NOT the life for you. Responsibility, hard work, and critical thinking are pretty difficult skills. What if you could just not do that? You tell the patient that you need to go grab some supplies from your bunk and that you'll be right back. Taking as many supplies with you as you can, you flee from the clinic and hurry to the bunk room. You pack up all of your things in a rucksack and cut open a blood bag and dump it on the bed to make it look like there was a struggle. You then wait until no one is around and flee the settlement. After exploring the nearby area for a few days, you're scavenging for food in a forest when you're ambushed by a small group of thugs. They angrily demand that you hand over everything you're carrying, or else. Instead, you bargain with them. You tell them that you were a doctor before the bombs fell, and that your skills are indispensable in the Wasteland. They could kill you if they want, but you're worth more to them alive. The thugs consider this for a second and decide that you're right. They escort you back to your camp, where your lies and charisma allow you to quickly rise through their ranks. Before long, you find yourself playing leader to a small yet vicious group of Wastelanders who survive by stealing and killing.

Biff Bronson's Wacky Wasteland Adventures! (TM)

PLAY-THROUGH RESULTS ---------------------

Scenario Generated: Sharing is Caring You shoot at the thief, fatally this time. The bullet hits her straight between the eyes. She falls to her knees with an expression of disbelief on her face. She's dead on the spot. You reclaim your belongings and return to your camp triumphantly. However, you can't help but feel like you could've resolved this in a less...deadly way. Maybe the punishment wasn't equal to the crime. But hey, you're eating Salisbury steak tonight!

Biff Bronson's Wacky Wasteland Adventures! (TM)

PLAY-THROUGH RESULTS ---------------------

Scenario Generated: The Good Doctor You hand the patient a sugar pill. Truthfully, this pill will do absolutely nothing, but it would be a waste of resources and potentially harmful to the patient if you medicated someone who wasn't truly physically ill. The patient takes the pill under the guise that it is a "cure all" for psychosomatic symptoms. The next morning, you wake up to a commotion outside of one of the sleeping quarters. You venture outside and see a number of settlers carrying out what looks like a body wrapped in a white sheet. However, they did a bit of a shoddy job, and you can see a shoe peeking out from the shroud. You swear that it looks exactly like the shoes the patient was wearing the day before. But surely you weren't wrong! After all, his condition wouldn't have been able to progress that quickly even if you were wrong! Yet, he doesn't return to the clinic that day. You begin to wonder if maybe it really WAS the patient's body that you saw that morning. You continue to tell yourself that coincidences happen all the time, and that he's surely better now.

Biff Bronson's Wacky Wasteland Adventures! (TM)

PLAY-THROUGH RESULTS ---------------------

Scenario Generated: Sharing is Caring You point into the distance behind the thief and shout, "Hey, look over there!" She turns around, befuddled, asking, "What? Where?!" While she's distracted, you quickly gather your things and hurry back to your camp. She's so intent on figuring out what was over "there" that she doesn't even notice. Upon returning to your tent, you quickly back up what little things remain and book it. It's time to start over somewhere else, but at least you're no worse off for it.

Biff Bronson's Wacky Wasteland Adventures! (TM)

PLAY-THROUGH RESULTS ---------------------

Scenario Generated: The Good Doctor Somehow, your high risk, low reward method pulled through. The patient slowly wakes up from his pain-induced faint, and looks down to see his missing limb. Out of fear for his life, he takes off and runs from the clinic. A week later the patient returns, reporting that he's feeling significantly better. He thanks you for making the difficult decision, and says that while he has no idea how this worked, it ended up paying off. Despite the odds, the patient was cured.

Biff Bronson's Wacky Wasteland Adventures! (TM)

PLAY-THROUGH RESULTS ---------------------

Scenario Generated: Atomic Adam You point at the horizon behind Atomic Adam and say, "Hey, look at that!" He turns around asking, "What? Where? I don't see anything." Without further ado, you turn around and sprint away in the opposite direction of the village you came from. It's time to start a new life, far away from here. As you put more and more distance between you and the hill, you can hear Adam's booming voice in the distance saying, "There's truly nothing here, unless I need to get my eye checked!" You may not have saved the village, but you sort of saved yourself. That is, if you can find water somewhere else.

Biff Bronson's Wacky Wasteland Adventures! (TM)

PLAY-THROUGH RESULTS ---------------------

Scenario Generated: Meltdown At a loss as to an actual solution, you throw yourself into the reactor hoping that sacrificing yourself to the radiation gods will spare the whole vault. Somehow, someone heard your pleas. The emergency alert system shuts off, and miraculously, you find yourself still standing there, alive. You emerge from the reactor triumphant. Rick, the other engineer, enters the room to verify you actually fixed it. His eyes widen as soon as they land on you. "Uh, you're um...you're glowing!" he stammers out. You hurry to a mirror and see that you are glowing bright green! At the end of the day, you DID save everyone. Who knows, maybe this is a superhero origins story in the making!

Biff Bronson's Wacky Wasteland Adventures! (TM)

His face is still in a state of utter shock as he falls backward, dead as a doorknob. You don't celebrate your success for long. You scramble to disassemble the dam and let the water pour back to the village. When you return home, the townspeople hoist you up on their shoulders and parade you through the town as their hero. One of them thinks he's some sort of journalist that aims to "expose the truth." It's probably all bluffing, considering he doesn't have a paper backing him. I know you're probably tempted to just let this go, but I really don't think we should. The Family and the Showmen are ruthless. If these rumors start to catch, and trust me, they will, they'll weaken us. And then the others will use that as an excuse to get out of paying their dues. We'll go broke. Utilities will shut off, the Overgrown will spill in, the tourists will spill OUT, a lot of people will die, and Acee will crumble. That sound like a timeline you want? Just give me the green light, and I'll take care of it. A journalist can't write without blood in his veins. -B

<font face='$Typewriter_Font' size='18'> The Devil is in the details, this much is true. The story of it begins here. The key lies in the very beginning.    The blood that is spilled trickles upward.  Payment is inevitable even from those who have it all.  Health is the only commodity of the rich and the comfortable.  Death follows the clarity after the rush.  Sins of the son follow the godfather. </font>
<font face='$evaScript_Font'><font size='20'> All the money and power in Atlantic City. In the end, not a single person will hold my hand while I die.    Tony, I'm so sorry.

<font face='$76HandwrittenNeat_Font' size='16'> How can I be absolved if there is no priest to stand before me? How can I seek forgiveness in a world that no longer cares if I am guilty or innocent? I don't wish for forgiveness from a deity, from a person, or from anything corporeal. I wish I could forgive myself, but that's impossible.    I look at what the Blood has done to my body, and I feel nothing at all. No anger, no sadness, simply an empty resignation. This city was like clay to me. I could've shaped it any way I wanted. Instead, I cut off my own hands.    All those miles traveled, all those lives wasted...just for the empire to fall. Sometimes, you can do everything right, and the world still falls apart around you anyway. Irregardless, it's not like I had all the time in the world left. If the Blood hadn't killed me, time would've taken me.    If Tony's reading this...please, do the right thing. Do it for me.  </font>

<font face='$HandwrittenFont' size='18'>Dad,    If we're going to be staying in Appalachia, can we PLEASE expand the house? I don't think I can handle another night sharing a bunk with Abbie. Her snoring is horrific. Seriously, it sounds like a car's failing to start all night.    Hell, I'll even help you build it if I have to. I'm all excited for this whole "family" thing, don't get me wrong, but I need a break here.    Vin</font>

<font face='$76HandwrittenNeat_Font' size='18'>I can't let on to Evelyn just how much this is killing me. Ever since Abbie left, my head's been filled with this fog. It's like my brain's a car and the driver's slamming on the breaks. The answers to simple questions evade me. I often walk into rooms wondering why I went in there in the first place.    What scares me more than anything, is that these are the exact symptoms I first read about when I began researching dementia. Is this some sort of karma?! Can't let myself think like that. It's probably all just psychosomatic.    It's just stress, plain and simple.    </font>

<font face='$HandwrittenFont' size='18'>Mom,    I know you're worried, but everything has been fine. Seriously. I haven't so much as looked at Blood since I took the antidote. In fact, I've been thinking of following in your footsteps and getting back into music. I was hoping that it would be a good distraction, to channel my energy into something other than chems. Besides, busking could bring home a bit of income for me.    Regardless of what dad says, I'm not coming home. I made my decision. There's nothing for me in Appalachia. AC is and has always been my home. I'm sorry, but you and dad had SO many chances to make things right, and you never did.     Despite all this, I still love you. Even though I probably shouldn't.    -Abs</font>

<font face='$Typewriter_Font' size='14'>Vin,    I can't lie to you and say that I agree with your decision to go to Appalachia. While I admire persistence and the need to follow through on a cause, I only adhere to that mentality when the cause is just. To put it simply, it seems like you're barking up the wrong tree. But you're a grown man now. It's your life, your choices.    That being said, however, your absence here at City Hall will certainly be felt. One dimension to that is your work ethic and dedication. You've done a lot for this city, and that work certainly didn't go unnoticed.    The other side to it is...sentimental. We don't have a whole lot of folks willing to help out, as you know. So it's a pretty small group of us here, and it becomes a bit like a family. I don't say this easily, but in time, I came to look at you as if you were my own son. While I can't speak for her, I know Frieda feels the same way. Had things taken a different turn, I would've liked for you to have taken the reigns of mayor from me one day. But we can never predict how life turns out, can we?    Despite this, I know you have an obligation to your own kin. I wish you the best in the rolling green hills and endless blue skies of Appalachia. I can't thank you enough for everything you've done for this city, son. Just know that if you ever decide to return, you will always be welcome in the municipal office.    Sincerely,    Tim Lane</font>

<font face='$Typewriter_Font'><font size='30'> ROSE ROOM REVIEW  <font size='20'> Review by Bibbius Snibbius    <font size='18'> The Rose Room? More like the RUSSET Room, since this place is more of a ground tuber than a flower! As Appalachia's premier pseudonymous food critic and cuisine connoisseur, I made my way to the so-called "Rose Room" expecting a level of class not usually seen in this mountainous region. After all, the owners claim to be from Atlantic City, a bastion of civilization famed for its "high roller" lifestyle and luxurious accommodations.    The trek to the old "mansion", if it can even be called that, was onerous and dull. I hardly felt like the patron of a high-end establishment heading there, and more like a pilgrim performing some religious patronage for a brahmin steak and a whiskey.    Once I finally arrived at the "club", I was thoroughly disappointed in the architecture and atmosphere. It was inexcusably dirty, had clearly not been renovated, and the drapes were so abominable they could've been a second doomsday in of themselves.     I was greeted by a blonde woman in a garish dress who called herself Evelyn Russo and claimed to be the owner and proprietor of the Rose Room. I attempted to question her as to why she chose a rhododendron garnish for my molerat pate when everyone knows molerat pate is paired with mirelurk caviar. She looked at me as if I was a loon, and told me to just relax and enjoy the music.    Music! Oh, how Dean Domino would do barrel rolls in his grave to hear that drivel be called MUSIC! The only redeeming quality of it was the rather superb tuba-playing. Beyond that, some gas station knock-off of a lounge singer walked on stage and started crooning. By all that is holy and unholy, I did not need to hear what a scorchbeast in labor sounds like.    Not only were my ears bleeding, but every single one of my billions of taste buds were personally offended by the watered-down alcoholic beverages and flavorless "meals." The bartender, some young man with a haircut far trendier than him, came out and tried to placate me, offering a discount.    Why, never in all of my years as a food critic have I taken a BRIBE! I looked this man, "Vin", in the face and told him so! I let him know with no minced words that I shall be writing a review of this hovel, and no amount of caps could possibly sway my mind!    So here I am, penning yet another acclaimed review. The Rose Room is NOT worth your time or caps. I would rate it zero stars out of five. In fact, I would remove every single star from the sky myself, one by one, so that there are no stars left to give such a lackluster experience.    Until the next review, my dear readers. Let's hope it's not as pedestrian as this one.

<font face='$76HandwrittenNeat_Font' size='18'>Everyone knows. Their watchful eyes, their spiteful smiles... Why else would they look at me like that?    It's a game they're playing. Waiting for me to crack. Then they can all laugh together, all the Showmen, drown the protege before he can drag them down! He's a fraud! ME! I'm a fraud, a sham, a charlatan! It will never last... I'll be cooked on a spit! Skewered by their pointed fingers!     Is it wrong to cling to life? Is it not the truest instinct of man? What does it mean that all sound disappears at night and I bolt awake, scratching at my jugular, desperate to confirm that my heart still beats?    I must hide my ruse and survive. Smile, nod, fool them all. Flip the script! Now truth is doubt.    My charade has become my reality.

<font face='$76HandwrittenNeat_Font' size='18'>Mother says the Blood unlocks our true potential. So what does it mean that I float in the same vast abyss? For a blissful moment, the waves glowed every color, soft as silk, and I drifted weightless in an empty paradise. I met the one called Peace for the first and only time.    Then, the cacophony. Lights glaring! Voices shouting! Walls crashing back to perspective! Gravity's blunt and shocking force! Everything louder than before. The face of Danger, wholly revealed, staring back endlessly from each and every surface... and still He has not closed his eyes.    Yet nothing has awakened in Me. I breathe more terrified than ever before. I stumble more often. I open my mouth and cannot find the words it grasped just a moment before. Is this all my potential? Am I so much a failure?    It cannot be, it cannot... I just need to dive deeper and find it. Yes... I must have glimpsed something at the bottom of that abyss. There must be something magnificent there! I just need more, more than we've ever been allowed... But where? How? Every well has a source. I must find it and drink. Deeply.    Then... Only then I will be magnificent.

<font face='$evaScript_Font' size='18'><b>To the silliest of Star Clowns    I prepared your show outfit just the way you told me:    ... Donned the hat and outfit at midnight  ... Thought about my shortcomings and cried into the sleeves  ... Laughed hysterically for 10 minutes to fully dispel the bad humors  ... Did NOT wash the outfit  ... Filled the pockets full of posies  ... Placed it here with exactly eight balloons  ... Sang a song and danced around    This is certain to help you put on the best performance you've ever done! I promise I did it exactly as you wanted... so please dont punish me.

I'm beginning to regret signing up for this mission. All I knew was we were sent to salvage an old crashed vertibird, and set up a base on the nearby cliff. What I didn't think about was the ride over here. I still have no idea how our APC managed up and down that hillside. Lugging supplies the rest of the way up was the worst part. Luck started to change when reconnaissance came back saying there's a small moonshiner's shack just east of here. Davis and I snuck over there the other night and purchased a bit of the good stuff. By damn did we hurt in the morning though. Now we're hearing reports that cultists were seen wandering nearby and heading into a cave system. We've yet to check it out to see what they might be up to.

My name is Nathan Broadhurst, and here is my story of how I went from a famous baseball player, to a lonely but content old man.     I can still remember, clear as day when it all started. It was the morning before the big game-The World Series. It was us versus Texas. I showed up early with Jim Walker and Matt Murtagh. Matt had been worried sick, because he was first up to pitch, so Jim and I were helping him warm up. Little did we realize the biggest day of our life was larger than we expected. I was up to bat when we felt everything shake. Thank God for Fenway's massive walls, otherwise we woulda been toast. We assumed it was an Earthquake at first, until that terrible sound, and the burst of dust overhead. I remember watching half the chairs in the outfield being blasted to Hell.    Once the worst of it appeared to be over, Matt was in a rush to head back to Atlanta to make sure his family was okay. Never found out if he made it back or not. I went with Jim and headed West so we could meet up with my fiance Janice, who was also Jim's sister. They had grown up in Charleston West Virginia. We were originally gonna take a more coastal route, but we heard that New York was even worse off than Boston. We ended up taking Highway 90 onto 84 until we joined a group in Hartford who was heading to Pittsburg. Shortly after we parted ways in Altoona, Jim and I ran into some trouble.     It was this little town called Bedford which had already walled themselves in. Some bald putz came storming out with his group of assholes on bikes. They pinned us down, tied us up, and locked us in an old bank. Luckily it didn't take us long to cut ourselves free, find our bats, and get onto the roof, but when we jumped onto the next building, someone shot Jim mi-air. He was dead before he hit the street below. He'd been my best friend for years, and I had just watched someone shoot him like he was nothing. I had no choice but to run before they got me too.    It nearly took me another week to make it to Charleston. When I got here, no one had seen or heard from Janice in weeks. I searched for months, but never did find her. For all I know, we passed her on the way here. After a few years, I decided to settle down with a group of welcoming and bright eyed settlers. We built our home here on the cliffs, and it is here I am content to die.     I leave behind my story and my once famous bat in the hopes that it'll inspire or help anyone who needs it.

DESC: <font face='$HandwrittenFont' size='24'>Life just isn't worth living anymore without Keith. He was the most incredible, talented, brave, smart, funny person to ever live! And someone just killed him! What are we going to do without his guiding wisdom? We're all gonna die without him! </font>

<font face='$76HandwrittenNeat_Font' size='20'>What is a body to do without a brain? A car without a driver? Us without Keith?    I made a lot of stupid decisions in the past, but with Keith here to tell me what to do, and what not to do, it was all so much easier. Granted I couldn't do anything to benefit myself, but to benefit Keith was to help us all! How can he lead without eating the finest meats, drinking the best wines, and having the best company?     And now without him, we are lost. We are doomed.

<font face='$Typewriter_Font' size='16'> Dear Concerta,    How are you, darling? I do hope present circumstances haven't eroded the already tenuous sense of calm we've all been fighting to maintain.    I wanted to write to you candidly to inquire about the missing funds. The past few months, we've failed to receive the full amount owed to us for our entertainment services. I know you're a woman of integrity and wit. I also know all too well the vast challenge that comes with the burden of leadership. I mean no offense when I say that there are rats in your organization that may be sullying our friendship garden.    Since you are a bosom friend of mine, I will extend your deadline by a fortnight. Please ensure that we receive the rest of our owed expenses. Unfortunately, if I do not receive our dues by the aforementioned date, I will need to send some of my Showmen over to collect.    Best wishes,    Charlotte    (P.S. Are you still coming by for tea and coffee on Sunday? I just got my espresso machine working again).    </font>

<font face='$HandwrittenFont' size='14'>Like I said, this stays between you and me Murph. I'm not saying anything out loud in case the joint's bugged, so be sure to burn this letter.    I played cards with some of the guys who deliver the daily earnings into the vault. There's a ton of caps sure, but one guy gave me a tip. Swears he saw a whole crate of Devil's Blood that remains unaccounted for in any of the logs. Some kind of clerical oversight.    Think about it Murph. An entire crate of the stuff just left behind. A crimson treasure ripe for the taking.     Even if someone got the Blood, not many folks are willing to fence the stuff. The Family's got an iron grip on the Devil's Blood brewing and distribution in Atlantic City. If anyone outside the Family tries to sell it, they're signing their own death warrant.     But there's a lot of caps in it for someone who can. That's where you come in Murph. I'm familiar with your work back in Nevada when there were casino's worth robbing. Can't think of anyone better to break in and lift the stash.     If you manage to get that crate out, I'll show you my magic trick where I turn Blood into caps.

After every show, he heads over to the bar in the high roller lounge and starts flirting with all the old money there. He'd seduce a bar stool if it had a rich family.     Every night, he's ending up in someone else's room, and the next morning he's off pawning their valuables.    Sounds like the kind of guy I need.    Update  Ryder's In  </font>

If the opportunity sounds enticing, consider meeting me in room 101 at the Neapolitan.    Burn after reading.  -AM
