<font face='$HandwrittenFont' size='20'>If Muni's come sniffing around asking about rumors of there being Overgrown in the basement, you tell them nothing, capiche? You call the top lady, and she'll handle them.   If a guest asks about Overgrown sightings in the Casino Quarter, you give them the usual spiel assuring them the Neapolitan is and always will be a safe and secure place to spend their hard-earned caps. Give them some drink tokens on the house if you think it'll grease the wheels.</font>

Chapter 12 - Neapolitan Nitwit

While documenting the incredible journey of my life, It's important for me to document both my triumphs, and my failures. And boy howdy is this one triumphant failure. I should have known there was no way I was going to pull a stunt like that on Quentino's sister without consequences. Things were going so well too. I gave her the ol' Ryder charm after my show. The plan was to give her my patented shoulder rub, and that'd be my chance to lift the key. I blew it though. She saw right through my bullshit, and caught me making a grab for the vault key. Last thing I see is the butt of a gun clocking me in the skull. They kept me in a dark room and beat the names out of me. Soon as they started hitting the moneymaker, I cracked real quick. I have no regrets. That mafioso and that sorry Muni fella would have done the same. Frankly, I'm just grateful those thugs didn't break anything too important. I can get by on crutches for a long while. I've been blacklisted from the Casino Quarter. So I'm heading back to Showmen's pier. Maybe they'll take pity on me and let me sing the opening to that game they're always running. After writing it all out, maybe this one shouldn't make it to the autobiography.

Power Production & Management Division ==================== Neapolitan Monthly Power Consumption Report

Frieda, The Neapolitan continues to comply with power rationing standards set forth by the Power Production & Management Division of the Atlantic City Municipal Government. I have also personally approved the power saving plans proposed by the management at the Neapolitan for the next 6 months. It should accommodate a 4% drop in service, meeting our projected generator downtime. To address your concerns about the reported 8% overdraw, this can be attributed to an instrument failure.
Finding a pristine replacement these days is difficult. Rest assured; I correct for this error in my weekly reports. Dean Carlsen PPMD Supervisor for the Neapolitan

As we make for Appalachia, remember one thing: the people we will meet there are our comrades in arms. Those of us who survived the Bombs remember that before the Great War, laborers across this great country were fighting our own, more personal struggle -- and not against the Reds. Quite the opposite! No, in the middle of a battle for human existence, industrial overlords like the Hornwrights insisted on tearing our livelihoods from us in the name of 'efficiency!' We refused to take it lying down, and not just in Pennsylvania. Have you ever heard of Beckley, West Virginia? Labor rose up. They couldn't take it anymore, and they fought back! These people and their descendants are the ones who will welcome us to Appalachia. Remember that when things get tense... We're all cut from the same cloth. We can work together for a better tomorrow.

Delta, I'm making an adjustment to your usual patrol route. Rather than the typical loop around the perimeter, I'd like you to expand your radius to include the road nearby. We've cleaned up the debris in the immediate vicinity, and the station has been secure for the last few days, but reports from Alpha indicate increased traffic -- hostile or otherwise -- along that artery. Between Scorched, raiders, cultists, and the odd robot, it should be a fertile training ground for some of our greener troops. I know that's not strictly in line with our core mission, but I feel quite strongly that we need an effective fighting force at Tango to tackle any unforeseen circumstances that may arise. That said, this is still a patrol, not a search and destroy mission. Don't go out of your way and endanger yourselves looking for action. I expect to see you back at base safe and sound tomorrow morning, just with a little more experience under your belt. Ad victoriam, Initiates.

Adelaide, Dear sister, I hope this letter finds you well. I hope it finds you at all... If not, then it's good therapy I suppose, though small comfort. I have many regrets about how we parted, but I hope you and father will forgive me for my arrogance. I believed wholeheartedly that fighting those bandits was the right course of action. I saw you both as cowards, unwilling to stand up for yourselves. A disastrous outlook. I should have joined you on that caravan while I had the chance. Instead, I lost my family and nearly lost my life. I've settled in well with a group here in Appalachia that call themselves the Responders. They're good people, and they want to build a peaceful world, like how home used to be. I believe in their mission, and though it will be a long road I think we will at least be able to carve out a little niche of civilization for ourselves. Because I (regrettably) have some combat experience, they're calling me a 'constable,' and asking me to keep the peace. I empathize with the mission, but I'm not a fan of the title. It's not who I am anymore, but I didn't want to protest; they've been so good to me. I hope that one day you and father will return from wherever that caravan has taken you, and I can show you the home we're building here. You don't have to stay, but maybe it will convince you that your brother's not such a bastard after all. If that's too much to ask, then I apologize. Wishing you the best regardless, Lane

Hi Rucker! Madam Rucker? General? Quartermaster in Chief? Anyway, just sending in my usual report. We have scavenged... quite a lot of unusual junk, much of it very unhelpful when it comes to, you know, surviving. For instance, my records indicate only six cans of Cram, but nearly ninety bottles of beer! Which is great for morale, and for keeping our lookouts so cross-eyed they couldn't see the Scorched coming from a mile away, but not so great for nutrition. I also have to say -- and I apologize if I'm stepping over the line here -- but I do not agree with this policy we have of giving away all of our bandages and canned goods in the name of 'world peace' or whatever we want to call it. I know, I know, I need to bring it up with Lane... I've tried being passive aggressive about it (emphasis on passive, of course), but he hasn't taken the hint! Maybe you could send him your own passive aggressive letter? Emphasis on aggressive? Please? It would be very helpful. Signed, Your humble servant June Seaver, Esq.

Top Secret! For Blue Ridge eyes only. That means don't leave this one lying around for any old passersby to see. I think it's about time we get an in with those Responder folks in the Whitespring (or Refuge, whatever they're calling it these days). It's incredible to say, but somehow these people have managed to get tied in with all kinds of groups well outside of Appalachia. That's a lot of potential markets opening up that we aren't a part of, all because of that Vertibird. We need to convince them that a partnership will benefit us both. Sell them on our experience, on our infrastructure. Remember: they're the 'little guy.' We have a big head start in the trading business, and they aren't even all that interested... yet. By getting in early, we could nip a competitor in the bud. If you can do anything to butter them up, it could be beneficial in the long run. Maybe we can start by helping out that new outpost of theirs at the lumber mill near the Wayward? Just a thought. Stay safe out there.

<font face='$HandwrittenFont' size = '18'>Whoever finds this, my name was Cyrus Kingdom. I was a student of geology at VTU investigating local stories of folks pulling blood red ground water. I found some old surveys in Charleston calling it the "Organ Cave", supposedly named after a stone fixture that resembles a pipe organ. The stories were right though. Blood red water.     Couldn't be nothing more than the water lingering on top of a large iron ore vein, then making its way to the groundwater I figured. I still couldn't shake off the feeling that it was a bad omen. Maybe I should have listened to my gut on this one.    While mapping this cave out, I felt the earth shake around me, and next thing I know I'm trapped in a cave in. Earthquake? The world ending? Doubt I'll ever know.    If I'm ever found after I'm gone, I want my remains to be buried near home. Don't leave me in this hellish place.    Love you Ma. Love you Pa.  </font>

<font face='$HandwrittenFont' size='19'>A vulture has come to my city. He does not kill, but shepherds prey to their death. For what feast would there be in a quick and easy demise? No... For him, the feast is their struggle. Dessert is when the last glimmer of hope leaves their eyes.    He has yet to find his place. It's different here in the city, where a semblance of order keeps the ignorant populace at peace. Yet he has come here, and thus with a reason. Searching, yearning... for a nest to call his own.    Mother welcomes you, my child. This world would call you a monster. I would call you my own. I would give you a calling. Do you hear me, child? In destruction there is creation! Direct your impulses; channel them toward a higher pursuit! I can see the shape of it now... A venue for others like you, others with hunger. A place for them to be free!    In this, you shall never be alone again.    Mother welcomes you home, sweet Veracio.

<font face='$76HandwrittenNeat_Font' size='20'>I have no hope left.    Spent every last dollar at the Neapolitan. Was gonna use the winnings to pay back my debts. Pay the rent. Give Margot a reason to stick around. A reason to believe in me.    I'm so damn tired of being the loser. Can't keep a job, can't keep a place, can't keep my head out of trouble for two days. Every time I break away from something, it comes back to haunt me.     I bet everything to turn it around. Now I've got nothing left to bet. Nothing except...    I keep hearing about this game. Some crazy death race. Seems nobody in their right mind would do it. Yet people do. Thrill-seekers. Addicts. Losers like me. I've seen them come out on top... Be celebrated. Be the hero for once in their lives. Could that really be me, too?    Everything else is gone... but maybe I do have one last thing I can bet.

FULL: Do You Want To Feel Alive?
DESC: <font face='$Typewriter_Font' size='16'>Are you bored? Down on your luck?    Does your life lack meaning?    Do you seek wonder and excitement? Fame and riches?    Do you wish to be the STAR of the show?    Now you can, by playing THE MOST SENSATIONAL GAME!     Where every player is the star!     Every star is the master of their own fate!     And anyone's fate... can be changed in an instant!    Sign up today - select evenings on the Boardwalk! All participants must bring their own weapons.

<font face='$HandwrittenFont' size='19'>A single victory is cause for celebration. Two is proof. Three or more, and we may deign to call it arrogance.    Yet I cannot help but admire these orphans, for such a show they've put on! The boy stands tall against every resistance. Guarded by his tenacity, the girl sneaks through every trap. No doubt she'll soon start setting her own.    Try as I might to bring these prodigies under my wing, they claim they have no need for family save each other. How a doting Mother's heart breaks!     For a child that cannot be tamed is a naughty one.    I must find a handler, and soon, lest my darling Veracio's Game becomes a farce! The masses of this ailing city present such lackluster competition! Perhaps from the outside, we can find a challenger worthy enough to put them in their place.    To heel these naughty orphans, and breathe some spirit back into the waiting crowds. They sleep with their eyes open, blind to their own potential! How many times have I said that anyone can be a star?    Anyone who is willing to risk it all - life, limb, and soul - for a chance to see their own glory.

<font face='$HandwrittenFont' size='20'>Been ages since I felt this excited. The raider pits don't do it anymore. I beat every last one... Now the cowards hear my name and refuse to participate. Seems nobody has the guts to challenge themselves. Leaving me with not a single damn fighter to pummel!    So one day this flyer washes up at our camp, all dirty and half ripped to pieces. Some kind of Game in Atlantic City - bring your own weapons. Now I'm here, and the stories don't disappoint. Competitors dead and maimed, others crowned and showered in riches. The strong come out on top!    It's my time to shine, baby. After tonight, call me SENSATION!

FULL: Plan: Fasnacht Veggie Man Beer Stein
Urgent message for R. Dunwich and C. Blackhall
DESC: <font face='$Typewriter_Font' size='16'>Urgent message for R. Dunwich and C. Blackhall:    Nate knows too much. His followers are growing, and his word is convincing. Although most everything they're saying is speculation, a lot of it is based in collected facts. It's a good thing this information didn't get out before the war.    The followers could be converted if they're not too dangerous. They could serve our cause well.   </font>
<font face='$HandwrittenFont'><font size='15'>Knock once for Concerta  Twice more for old Quentino  Add a knock to ward off the traitor  And let yourself in    Don't ask me how it works.

<font face='$HandwrittenFont' size='18'>Alright, Surly, you know the drill.    It took a hell of a lot of spiked Buffout, but I think we finally have this Hunter guy down for the count. We'll take him back up to the Crosshair and Rob can decide what to do with him.    Maybe we'll make him our jester. Seems like a funny guy. Seems like a waste to eat such a scrawny man.  </font>

<font face='$76HandwrittenNeat_Font' size='19'>I can't stand Brutus anymore. He used to be my big, dumb protector. Now he's become a big, dumb nuisance.    At first I didn't think it was him. Some stolen makeup, dresses bunched differently than how I left them. Could have been a rabid fan, or another dancer who got jealous. Then he started locking doors. Turning off lights. I was trapped in the dark for a whole night, and that's not even the worst of it. Imagine my shock when the lights came on to a dead radrat on the vanity!     Who else could be capable of such a thing? It hadn't even been shot; its neck was twisted. And the lights, the keys... Only Brutus has access to those. Him and the janitor.    I can hardly take it anymore. Things used to be perfect. All I wanted was the attention of one special man. Not Brutus... Never Brutus. He should know who he is by now.    Just a big, dumb nuisance.

<font face='$Brody' size='18'>Dear Cast Members,    I must extend a heartfelt thank you for your efforts during this first week of rehearsal. My eyes, having been bored to literal tears by your lackluster performances, are now wide open to the reality of how little talent I have to work with. Without witnessing your infantile gesticulations, wooden imitations of emotion, and masterful ability to misinterpret stage blocking, I would never have accepted what needs to be done to bring this production up to standard.    In an effort to unearth some semblance of the written characters from your oblivious egos, you are all required to practice method acting from now until the end of the production. Forget who you were up until this point. Trust me when I tell you that they weren't worth knowing anyhow.     You ARE Stella, the gorgeous burlesque dancer.     You ARE Stratton, the no-nonsense businessman.    Brutus, you were close already. Just remember to discard any half-intelligent thought that occurs to your tiny little brain, and replace it with lovely Stella. She is the ONLY thing that matters to you, and you haven't the faintest clue how to show it.    I look forward to seeing this love triangle in action tomorrow. If I see a hint of any of the lackluster actors I made the mistake of hiring, the whip is coming out.    With Love, Your Director

<font face='$Typewriter_Font' size='16'>We couldn't find Stratton after rehearsal. Gone without a trace. Really strange, considering how reliable he always was. A guy like that doesn't run away. Maybe someone kidnapped him from backstage? The strange part is I couldn't find any signs of a struggle. In fact, the area was the cleanest I had ever seen it before.    In any case, that makes for an empty curtain call. Two actors dead, one spirited away. We'll need a whole new cast for the next production.    Shame, that. I was starting to like them.    What were their real names again?

To whatever sweet, wonderful, caring soul may come across this letter... You gotta get me outta here! My name is Gene, I been held captive by the Family for... er... well, a good long while at least. Hard to remember when you're so full of Devil's Blood that you may as well be the Jersey Devil itself. I'm a chem cook. Yeah, I said it! Damn near the best one in Atlantic City, too. Which is why they've had me makin' Blood for them for as far back as my very short term memory goes. Day and night, nothin' but cookin', cookin', cookin'. It's outta control! I got no privacy and no life! So anyway, my daring, dashing heavily armed knight in shining armor... Come to my rescue, why don't ya? I'll be waiting! Gene

<font face='$76HandwrittenNeat_Font'> Tony,    You're probably never going to read this, are you? It's the most hopeless feeling in the world, I tell you, just scribbling into the void while I can practically feel my body giving in from the inside out knowing that you'll never even lay eyes on this piece of paper.    I know you feel like you let me down, but the truth is, I let you down. I was supposed to watch your back, keep an eye out for you. I lost track of things, and it all started spiralling out of control. If I could turn back time, I would've burned that first shipment of Blood. But we both know I can't do that.    It's poisonous, the damn thing. It's like the sweetness of sugar coursing through your blood. But just like how sugar rots teeth, there's something about this chem that decays your blood, makes it ache. Everything that flows through me aches.    I should've been alive to hand the reins of la cosa nostra to you personally. I should've been well enough to stand up and declare your authority. But I wasn't. And it's all my fault.    I'm sorry, kid. I really am. I saw dollar signs, and in the end I screwed us both.    </font>

<font face='$HandwrittenFont' size='14'>    Billy,    I have good news and I have bad news. The good news is that you'll have less inclement expenses to account for going forward. The bad news is that things got a bit messy last night, and I'm going to need a trunk. Not the elephant kind. I've learned to be more direct after last time.    -C    </font>

<font face='$Typewriter_Font'><font size='24'> DEATH NOTE    <font size='16'> Patient Name: Lombardi, Quentino    Time of Death: 22:54    CMO (Y/N): Y    Autopsy Request (Y/N): N    Physical Exam: Patient was in incoherent mental state upon arrival. Body temperature exceeded 38 degrees Celsius. Sweated excessively and was unable to lift extremities without aid. Preliminary examination denotes no dermal or skeletal injuries. Patient was suffering from nonstop tremors.    Attendees: One attendee present, Concerta Lombardi.    Family Notified: The patient's sister was present for his death.     Patient Expire Within 24 Hrs of Admission (Y/N): Y    Medical Examiner Contacted (Y/N): N (see notes)  Notes: Upon request of family    Description: Patient was suffering from severe withdrawal symptoms in what appears to have been an unsuccessful attempt to wean off of Devil's Blood. The patient's sister called for medical attention, but nothing could be done short of making the patient more comfortable. The patient went into cardiac arrest after three hours of surveillance and passed away. Advanced age likely worsened his condition. Patient's sister admitted to having administered Addictol prior to my arrival, but the chem had no effect on the patient's condition.    Signed,    </font>    <font face='$Brody'>    Dr. Frank Vitelli, MD    </font>

<font face='$HandwrittenFont'><font size='18'>Let me spell it out for you BOZOS.  "Operation Bluebell" will be taking place on Thursday. Not Wednesday like Jimmy was saying. THURSDAY. If nothing else gets through your thick skulls, just remember Thursday.    Why do you need to remember Thursday? Because that's the day you need to stay AWAY from the rehearsal hall.   Boss has some plans for that "rising star" Adelaide and wants to see if they can't get their money's worth from her with a secondary purpose.    If you hear music on Thursday, congrats, you're an idiot who can't follow instructions. RUN AWAY! She's been upgraded with a remote receiver for an unforgettable show.    Got it? Good. If you have questions, read this note again.
<font face='$Terminal_Font'>  Dear (INSERT NAME HERE)          Thank you for your continued support!              X0X0  ADELAIDE    </font>

<font face='$76HandwrittenNeat_Font' size='20'>  The world has gone to all hell, but miners still spend every waking hour hunting for riches in the jagged stone of Appalachia. Some things never change.    Every waking hour? Not quite accurate. For when the sun sets, their minds turn to other things -- chems, gambling, booze. I find myself entrapped in this den of debauchery. I'm not immune to its charms.    Besides, I came here for info. A lead on Little Rob, that notorious bandit who stalks the hills nearby, and I can tell I am close. Surly, the ringleader here, has said as much.    She insists I take chem after chem. This pill and that pill slide down my throat, lubricated by more whiskey than I knew existed. Untold doses of Buffout fill my veins. I'd say it's the price I pay for my art, but we all know I'd be lying. I enjoy it all too much to call it a toll.    I can't get enough of the stuff, and if they'll give it out for free, then why not partake? I get what I want and then some.  </font>

<font face='$76HandwrittenNeat_Font' size='20'>Oscar,    Seems you didn't get the memo the first time. Well, here it is: proof definitive that I'm whole, healthy, and unharmed. You're welcome.    This errand runner you sent after me... Intriguing person, I admit, but they screwed up big time. Came in guns blazing, blood everywhere... the story would be much more robust if they hadn't splattered the brains of those poor fools I'd slipped in with all over the cave wall.    Luckily, they made up for it. In fact, without them it may have been my brains splattered by Little Rob, so in the end I have to thank you for sending them my way. Of course, you could have come up here yourself (you lazy bastard), but nonetheless...    I got the story, and with that I'm off. You probably want me to come down to the Crater and meet up with you, but that's a no go. Once the Eagles find out we murdered half the Crosshair the target on my back will be too big to hang out in a raider haven.    I'm going to the rendezvous point. You know the one. I'll meet you there and then it's on to the next gig.    Don't keep me waiting,  Jack  </font>

<font face='$Typewriter_Font' size='20'>  The "Blood Eagles..." a name cursed as much by its origin as by its present reputation. You need to be a sick fuck to be a Blood Eagle. Dangerous. Depraved. Whacked out on Buffout, Psycho, Daddy-O and anything else you can get your hands on. That's not an exaggeration... it's a requirement.    In this gang, the sickest of the sick fucks rise to the top. At the Crosshair, an isolated stronghold high in the crags of northern West Virginia, that would be Little Rob -- a nasty human being, but a fascinating one.    In the Blood Eagles, those who control the chems control the universe, and Rob is sitting on the biggest stash of Psycho this side of the Appalachians. Needless to say he has an iron grip on the Crosshair gang -- for now. Power passes from one boss to another at the drop of a hat. Rob won his stash in a hand of poker (or so he tells it), and he could lose it the same way. Gambling is rampant in the Crosshair, even at the top.    Chem taking is an important ritual for the gang. Most of its members are hooked on the stuff, and that's no accident. In fact, it's their preferred method of "recruitment." Masquerading as one profession or another, they lure the unsuspecting into a game of chance, ply them with libation, then manipulate or bully their target into dosing up on wild, spiked up shit.    Then it's off into the mountains with you, where you're pressganged into the club or sliced up and eaten in stir fry. In this way, most Eagles begin as addicts, fed a slow drip of substance to maintain their dependency on the gang. Over time, they start to blend in. They'll do anything for the chems -- anything. And addiction doesn't help their moral judgment in the long run.  </font>

<font face='$76HandwrittenNeat_Font' size='20'>  Somehow I've made it right to where I want to be. Alive, in the lion's den, surrounded on all sides by the worst mankind has to offer.    They consider me a prize, a convert to win over. I'm a joke to them, a distraction. What they don't realize is that they are targets too.    I won't call myself a hunter. To entertain such a thought is folly of the highest order. I'm completely at their mercy, and under no illusion that they could snuff me out at any opportunity.    But that doesn't change the fact that I want to be here, and the less threatening they find me the better. Getting in with the gang is key to getting in with their boss, and he is the real treasure of these hills.  </font>

<font face='$HandwrittenFont' size='14'>    God, I hate math.    It's just five digits, Billy. You can do this.     First letter of each line of that stupid poem, then match 'em up with the tax records.     This is the worst job ever.    </font>

FULL: Plan: Slab of Ground Meat Plushie
Plan: Weather Control Station (Atlantic City Fog)

DESC: <font face='$HandwrittenFont' size='14'>    To my unknown ally,    Murphy's Law details that everything that could possibly go wrong will go wrong, but what about the unforeseen that could go right? Of course, if you asked Fabio Mondadori, I'm sure his ghost would tell you this all went wrong.    I don't know who you are, or why you killed him, but it behooves me to thank you in excess. Although we are strangers, I owe my life to you. The best I can give is an unwavering friendship.    Best regards,    Concerta Lombardi    </font>

<font face='$HandwrittenFont' size='14'>    To my most consequential friend,    My time on this earth has made me an incorrigible cynic. When we first met, I certainly did not expect you to stand by my side. A complete stranger, and one universally hated by her own organization at that. The odds were against our partnership.    Nevertheless, you surprised me. You gave me a chance. Even at my age, there are experiences I had not yet gone through. No one, not even my own brother, ever gave me the opportunity to prove myself. To rise above my birth and carve out my own path. At every attempt, I was faced with not only opposition, but my own death.    Here I am, still breathing. And here you are. Of course, I don't know your intentions. Maybe you saw something in me. Maybe you just hated Fabio Mondadori. (Who could blame you?) Either way, your actions benefitted my interests, and it would be rude of me, neigh cruel, to not say thank you.    That would be the ultimate purpose of this letter. To say thank you. For everything. You will always have a friend in Atlantic City.    Best regards,    Concerta Lombardi    </font>

<font face='$HandwrittenFont' size='15'>Dearest Stephanie,     I'm hoping this letter doesn't find you, because I'm assuming you've moved like most other sensible people.     It's taken me ages to convince Irving that it's not getting any safer around here. Not to mention those horrid green creatures keep lurking in the shadows, and there seems to be more of them every day. The other districts are so much better off, and he's finally agreed to move to the Boardwalk.     It's a shame to leave our old home behind. This apartment was a blessing before the war, and we were high above when it flooded. But ever since the stairs fell through, and Irving had to repair the bridge for a third time, this place just isn't worth the hassle. We're getting old, and I'd rather live comfortable for the years we have left.    Until we meet again, Vickie

<font face='$76HandwrittenNeat_Font'>Things have been different since the painter's association dissolved. Well, who am I kidding? They've been different ever since the War. They didn't feel that different, thanks to the Munis holding everything together. But it makes sense they could only invent work for a dying profession so long. It doesn't matter what color your wall is anymore, only that it's still standing.    Despite it all, I'm grateful. Me and Pa are learning new skills. They need more hands to help patch up holes in City Hall, mop up floods, repair pipes. And I've resolved to ask the Forestry Division for arms training. Things are getting more dangerous around here.    I guess that means my old life has ended. But it's not over. Now I'm embarking on a new one. No matter what happens, my spirit will live on in the city I call home. In the hearts of those I care about. That gives me the strength to face this new world with my head held high.    No more looking back. Onward and upward.    Nick

<font face='$HandwrittenFont' size='15'>  Warning!!!!!    Supply Tunnels are closed until further notice. Three employees have gone missing and have not returned as of Yesterday. There have been numerous reports of some "thing" lurking down there. We believe these are just hallucinations and the wild accusations that there is a "Demon" down there is Preposterous. We are men and women of science, not crazed Superstitious fools.    We are looking for volunteers to go on a rescue mission to find the missing personal. We belive there could have been a cave in and they are trapped. Please report to Mike if intrested.

<font face='$HandwrittenFont' size='20'>    Dear Mr. Johnson,    We are contacting you on behalf of our client, to inform you that any further delays on the construction will result in the termination of our contract. As foreman, we expect you to handle this and honor our deal. This will be your third and final warning.

<font face='$HandwrittenFont' size='16'>  STOCKLIST    2x Radstag Meat  3x Mole Rat Feet  10x Potato Crisps  30x Canned Dog Food  3x Psycho (RESERVED)  2x Day Tripper (RESERVED)    LISTEN UP, THIEVIN ASSHOLES! Whoever stole that Mole Rat Foot is gonna pay. Bring it back now or when I find ya, I'll saw your foot off and feed it to the crew instead.

Camp Diary  October 23, 2077  Saturday     Dear Diary,  Today, I am going over to the Shenandoah National Park with my fellow Pioneer Scouts for a weekend camping trip. Normally, we only get to see Camp Liberty during the summer, so I'm excited to see what it looks like when the leaves are changing.  [pagebreak]  Mom says that this camp is for survival training. She says I can try archery, orienteering (whatever THAT is) and hunt real animals with a REAL gun!      Our Scout leader Mr. Mitchell is currently driving us to camp. He says that if we're lucky, we can meet the camp counselors when we arrive!  [pagebreak]  I am not sure how Mr. Mitchell will deal with all of us by himself. He has already shouted at Thomas twice for distracting him while he drives.         I will write more tonight, I can't wait to see what this trip has in store for us...

<font face='$HandwrittenFont' size='15'>Happy Birthday (my gorgeous) Thomas,    I hope you have an amazing 12th birthday with your friends at camp and doing all sorts of exciting and educational activities. I know it's not exactly what you wanted to do but your dad means well sweetheart. He really is trying his best to adjust after the divorce.    When you come back home, Harry and I will take you to your favorite ice cream parlor and you can finally open all these presents piled up at your dad's house.    Harry and I love you so, so much. Have a super fun time and a lovely birthday. I can't wait to see you!    Love Mom and  (Step Dad) Harry</font>

<font face='$HandwrittenFont' size='17'>Happy birthday Sport,  I know It was my weekend to have you, but a couple of the guys wanted to go to Atlantic City. I couldn't just pass up on that.     It sure is lucky your scout group had a special weekend trip - thought we only got to send you off during the summer! Hopefully a good sign for how I do at the casinos, right? I know you'll enjoy camp more than hanging out with your old man. I promise that when I hit the jackpot, you'll get the best toy a 10-year-old could want.    From Dad.   PS. Your Mom and Harry will pick you up when its over.</font>

Your wife and kids are counting on you to do the right thing.   Don't disappoint us.    We know where you are...  Regards  W.

<font face='$HandwrittenFont' size='20'>  Memo   (Hopefully not my last...)    We were attacked by these... things, they're hard to describe. They almost looked electrically charged. We understood that going towards that storm would be dangerous but, hell, you can't expect that. I've got to find where the other group have set up camp and make it there, but I got a lot of land to cover...  [pagebreak]    If you find this note on my corpse, please take care of my cat. She doesn't deserve all this shit and she's not picky with food so you won't have to worry about her. Just give her some attention every now and then.    -Craig

<font face='$HandwrittenFont'> <font size='16'>  I'm writing this out so they don't hear us, but that lanky bastard has definitely been stealing from us. I left a screwdriver on the table when I was looking for our supplies and it was gone when I came back 10 minutes later. He needs to learn his lesson, Imma leave another tool back there and when he goes to collect it we'll teach him a lesson. Follow me round there in 10. Try not to be seen.  </font>

<font face='$HandwrittenFont'> <font size='14'>Dear Diary,</font>  <font face='$HandwrittenFont'> <font size='14'>Today has been a hard day. I miss the safety of Foundation... I'm not sure how I feel about this living situation, these are the same people that put heads on spikes, people in cages. How are we supposed to feel comfortable with these people around? I hope this weather clears up soon so we can get back, I have a bad feelin about all this.    Joyce  </font>

<font face='$HandwrittenFont'> <font size='16'>NOTICE</font>  <font face='$HandwrittenFont'> <font size='14'>If we're going to be holding out together we need to set some ground rules.    NO STEALING: if you're caught stealing you'll be ousted from both groups and the Storm will deal with you.    NO MURDERING: our main objective here is survival. <font face='$HandwrittenFont' size='14'>Camp Diary  October 24, 2077  Sunday     Dear Diary,  I made it to the camp last night, a bit shaken up but in one piece. I was greeted at the front by the camp counselors and some well-dressed men in suits. We explained the situation that transpired on the bus as well as the large explosion we saw. Two of the counselors were sent out to go help Mr. Mitchell who was still on the bus, while the others explained to us that they thought the explosion could have been a nuclear blast.     The well-dressed men left the camp shortly after we arrived due to losing contact with someone over the radio. The rest of us have been told to stay put and not leave the camp until help arrives. The counselors have been left in charge for the time being.      I am currently sharing a tent with some kids from the other scout group who have been here for a couple of days now. They are acting very strange and talking about weird topics I don't like. I assume it might just be nerves which is why they are acting odd. But some of the conversations they have freak me out.     The camp counselors are putting on a movie for us all to watch before bedtime, so I'm going to end the diary here tonight. I do hope my family are safe and I get to see them soon.

<font face='$Typewriter_Font' size='13'>                                                     ATTENTION: LET SLEEPING GIANTS LIE    Operation "Sleeping Giant"    Overview:    Operation "Sleeping Giant" has been set up to investigate the effects of communist radicalization and brainwashing on children. We believe that the communist state could use this method & tactic to gain a foothold in this country via creating sleeper cells.     The goal of the operation is to test the potency of brainwashing along with the short-term and long-term effects it has on sleeper agents over 5 to 50 years.      The test subjects will be controlled through the use of a trigger phrase, which will re-activate the brainwashed subject. The phrase is as follows "The sleeping giant awakes to find an unhappy world." accompanied with a loud bleep at the start and end.    We have secured a camp located in the Shenandoah National Park where the experiment will take place (away from public eyes). There will be at least one agent at the site at all times.      Reports need be sent back to headquarters on a monthly basis.

The bombs saved my life. If they hadn't dropped exactly then, well I'm not sure I would have gotten away from that lunatic that Hugo sent. Funny thing, that.    I wonder if Audrey even got my letter? Am I ever going to see her again? Did she make it to the Vault in time? Away from that psycho.

It's been a long day. No particular reason why, sometimes it's just like that right? Maybe one day we can get back to the point where a stroll outside can be calming again, but I don't see much light at the end of that tunnel just yet.

Johnny, We are pleased with the work you are doing as head of the Janitorial Department. It is not an easy task to keep a Vault of this size clean; the dedication of you and your staff has been noted and we are all thankful for your endeavors. That said, we have received numerous reports from security officers citing the "overly-curious" nature of several janitors in the Meteorology Sector. Might I remind you that there is much security-sensitive information in this area and that your staff are expected to keep their prying eyes and ears to themselves at all times. As head of this workforce, we trust that you will ensure this is the case in the future. Remember, as the old saying goes, "Ordnung ist das halbe Leben", or put plainly, "Order is half of life". From the desk of Hugo and Cassidy Stolz.

July 28th 2077    Papa never said we'd be living underground when we got here. He's always busy working now and I don't get to play with him much anymore. Mystery Disappearance

The town's been abuzz regarding a man said to have gone missing on his trip to our neck of the woods. Family say Quentin Hake was last seen on his visit to a West Virginia research facility on a business trip as an advisor for Stolz Enterprises. Beyond that, the family did not have further information on Mr. Hake's itinerary, or even the name of facility he was meant to visit. Cassidy Stolz, wife of CEO and founder Hugo Stolz, had this to say about the disappearance: [pagebreak] "We are extremely concerned to hear the news that Quentin has gone missing. He is a highly valued member of our workforce and we pride ourselves on putting employee well-being first. We hope and pray that Quentin will be found safe and sound as soon as possible." Stolz Industries has come up in the news a few times over the past few years after their purchase of large swathes of land in the Shenandoah National Park; much to the chagrin of the former residents, who famously held onto their land after a lengthy court battle against the state's claim of eminent domain. Stolz Industries declined to comment on their involvement with the supposed "research facility", or any dealings regarding their business in the Park that borders our great state. [pagebreak] Local law enforcement officials have initiated an investigation into the circumstances surrounding Hake's disappearance, and ask that any individuals with pertinent information report to the nearest police station as soon as possible.

October 18th, 2077 Poor darling Hugo, I haven't seen him this worked up in a long time. But who can blame him? He is only worried about his daughter's wellbeing, as any good father would be. I think he is just afraid of her impressionable mind being corrupted by the people around her. Still, I am not sure I agree with his solution to this problem. Unfortunately, he has already made up his mind, and once he gets like this there is simply no point in arguing with him. Let's just hope that Audrey never finds out the truth, or there'll be hell to pay. [pagebreak] February 13th, 2087 This Vault can be so claustrophobic. 10 years. So suffocating. I miss how much travel Hugo and I used to do. I miss all the different views. I miss the French Quarters and the music. I miss being surrounded by creative people. The people in here are also creative, but in a scientific way. Maybe one day we will be able to enjoy the world and the arts as we used to... My only sanctuary is the small waterfall in the Garden Sector - there I can pretend the world is still the same. Plus the sound of the running water soothes my mind whenever I start to feel unwell, which seems to be most of the time lately. I fear my condition may be worsening... [pagebreak] March 8th, 2087 God bless Hugo, but he can be so naive sometimes. He is too trusting, thinking that if he keeps the business within the hands of friends and family then he has no reason to worry. I ran into someone snooping around our office this afternoon. Said they were just "looking for a report", but I wasn't born yesterday. I've decided to lock away our more sensitive documents somewhere safe and won't be letting the key leave my person for any reason; luckily I have fashioned the key into part of my favorite necklace and it fits perfectly! No one needs access to these documents unless they have Hugo's or my permission anyway. As for this little detective I caught in the act... well, let's hope they can fake their way into a different Vault. [pagebreak] March 26th, 2087 Ach! I can't get any privacy in this wretched Vault: I was sitting in my happy place in front of the waterfall, finally reaching the deepest levels of my meditation, then guess who comes stomping right out from under there? Johnny, the head janitor, clunking around with a box of tools. Stupid man, just when I was finally starting to relax. I didn't even know we had a maintenance room back there! Still, it's good to know that there are some lesser-known areas down here. Perhaps I should let my darling Hugo know about this concealed area?

We ran into some cultists today while doing a pick-up job. Rest of those damn cowards fled. Left me, Patrick, Dustin and Hunter to these freaks.    They took us to some old mineshaft. Freezing down here now that all the adrenaline's settled.  [pagebreak]  Hell, I've done some sadistic crap with the crew over the years, but having it happen to our guys... makes me feel sick to my stomach. They took Patrick away. Didn't see him again but sure did hear him. Hell of an echo down here.  [pagebreak]  Seems they need to keep a few of us alive for some ritual, so they won't kill all of us, but that don't stop them from using us for fun. Cut us. Burn us. Bash our heads. Crush our fingers. Flay us alive. Taking stuff right out of our playbook, cept they spend the whole time praising some bug while doing it. But at least she sneaks us some scraps when they're not around.  [pagebreak]  If we ever get outta here, I'm done with the Blood Eagles. I can't be part of anything horrific no more. Can't do things like this to people. I need to get out. I'm scared, but I need to get out.    Someone's coming. Maybe this is my chance. I've got to try.

<font face='$HandwrittenFont' size='20'>As the mind responsible for the prototype, I feel it would be remiss of me to leave the workings behind these wondrous contraptions a mystery, so I have taken the liberty of writing a high-level overview of how this Lightning Harvester works.    Assuming all internal systems are normal and operational, initializing the Harvester's boot protocol will start the Storm Disruption Process.  [pagebreak]  During a cycle of heating & cooling, water droplets in the atmosphere become larger, inevitably rubbing against one another which causes friction and generates electricity. The harvester supplements this by discharging small amounts of electricity, using reserves kept from the last cycle.  [pagebreak]  This should lead to an increase in lightning strikes within the area - likely in a spectacular but dangerous fashion.    The Harvesters, however, are designed to be struck by lightning; when this happens they retain the charge from the lightning strike and store its energy in the custom silver-cored battery reservoirs built into the base of the harvester.  [pagebreak]  Alternatively, if needed, the machine can be set to send electricity directly back toward the Vault's various research departments.    Once sufficient energy has been gathered, the Storm Dissipation Cycle can be activated.

<font face='$HandwrittenFont' size='20'>While I am thrilled to be given the opportunity to see one of my creations come to life, I am startled and frankly concerned at the lack of safety & foresight my employers have shown.    My decision to use silver wiring was twofold; silver has high conductivity for electricity & heat, which means greater control over the heat generation sequence.   [pagebreak]  Unfortunately, I was under the impression these were prototypes; use of silver wiring introduces a serious long-term risk. Silver tarnishes far quicker than copper and thus becomes more unstable with use. The tarnished wires will eventually cause more resistance & heat, putting the integrity of the structures in jeopardy. Who knows how long these machines can last without regular wire replacements? A year? Maybe two?  [pagebreak]  Speaking of the heat generation, my second concern is with the venting chambers in the control bunker. They are exceptionally unorthodox; why would empty, unshielded rooms around the batteries aid the heat dissipation process that is designed to direct the heat into the ground? Those venting rooms are dangerous and should have the absolute minimum of human interaction, in my opinion. I was taken aback by the Overseer's insistence we use his old colleague's cooling design rather than my original one.  [pagebreak]  Not that anyone else seems to share my misgivings, of course. The Overseer wanted the most efficient machines possible and spared no expense, yet gave no thought to any of these concerns when I pressed the matter.  I was told a method of testing and disrupting the results of the "machine" could be of vital importance in the future. A machine they will not let ME look at, mind. Precious "Audrey" continues to receive special treatment while the minds of my ilk are put to use on busy work.  [pagebreak]  I also overheard something about the "obfuscation", which can only lead me to believe their pathetic attempts to disguise this place as a regular power substation has actually had some thought behind it. Whoever thought this would be passable should be put in one of those chambers during the next test run.

<font face='$HandwrittenFont' size='14'>Camp Diary  July 29, 2104  Tuesday    Dear Diary,  Today marked an unusually boring start to my day as I found myself assigned to the worst role possible: guard duty at the prison. While I sat there at my post, one of those capitalist insects walked over to the fence. A young girl with brown hair and a revolting knife scar tracing down her left eye (likely a captive from a Raider camp). She approached the fence and initiated a conversation with me. She bluntly inquired, "What led you to this path?" My immediate response was to command her to quit talking and return to her place, which she did with clear reluctance.  [pagebreak]  Her words stayed in my mind throughout the remainder of my shift. I couldn't help but think about the reasons behind my unwavering commitment to our cause. I've always believed, deep down, that our mission serves a greater purpose and paves the way for a brighter future. But I had never taken the time to truly question why I stood where I did. So, I thought writing down my reasoning here in my diary might be good for future reference.    Why wouldn't I desire a communist utopia? What has capitalism ever done for me, or the nation as a whole?    Capitalism stole my parents away from me. The government's greed and refusal to cooperate with China initiated the catastrophic war that ultimately claimed the lives of those dearest to me.  [pagebreak]  Capitalism replaced the hardworking people of this very state with cold, unfeeling robots. Generations of families who had slaved away in mines and various industries for years were callously discarded and replaced in an instant with cheap robotic help.    The privileged capitalist elite sought refuge in bunkers while the majority of hardworking citizens, who had empowered them, either perished or suffered through the nightmarish aftermath they left behind.    Should that boorish woman ever ask me again, I now have my answers. I am prepared to lay down my life for this cause, to fight for the creation of a new world from the ashes of the old one, a world designed for the many and not just the few. Our nation can be rebuilt and restored to its former greatness under this ideology.  [pagebreak]  I have never felt more certain about anything in my life than I do about this. Exhausted after my grueling 12-hour shift, I'm now leaving my diary here for the night. There's still the task of preparing food for tomorrow to attend to.

Dear Diary,  It's just me again, writing from my favorite spot. The smell of fresh flowers in the air mixed with the cool calming breeze on my skin, I just love spending time out here.  [pagebreak]  I promise, that one day I'll own my own beautiful gardens instead of tending to the Stolz family's. They're nice to us and all, but rumors have been spreading that we'll all be replaced by robots eventually. You know how Mr. Hugo cares for accuracy and efficiency...     Anyway, I better go before I get caught!

I feel like a character in one of them pulp horror magazines... I think I'm the only one left. And when I say "left," I don't mean alive, I mean not... turned. Something happened down in the Vault.   [pagebreak]  I can hear them outside, banging on the door and shrieking nonsense like "DEMONS" and "SPIRITS". They keep popping and sparking like someone stuck a fork in a power outlet. My terminal's power has been fried, and my lamp keeps flickering, too.    I'm afraid this door won't last much longer. I'm scared. Please God, don't make me one of them...

Secretary of the Interior Quarterly Visit

The Secretary of the Interior will be making their quarterly visit to Shenandoah National Park, scheduled for December 23rd, and has opted to stay here over the Christmas holiday. We are delighted that the Secretary has chosen to spend Christmas at Rapidan Camp. This trip coincides with their appearance at the Shenandoah New Year's Eve Party 2077; as a matter of national security, the Secretary has yet to announce that they will be spending time here over the holiday season, and the announcement is scheduled for the first week of November. Any information leakage will result in the termination of your employment, and you'll be dealt with appropriately.

Shenandoah Halloween Spectacular

As a thank you for all of your hard work over this past year, and to coincide with the White House's Annual Halloween festivities, you have all be given the evening off to attend the Shenandoah Halloween Spectacular party at the Shenandoah Visitor Center.

Shenandoah New Year's Eve Party 2077

The Shenandoah New Year's Eve Party has been announced and will occur here at Rapidan Camp. This year, the event is sponsored by Stolz Enterprises, with Mr. and Mrs. Stolz appearing for a speech during the event. Near the end of the evening, the Secretary of the Interior will make a special announcement about the future of Shenandoah National Park and future investments into the park. Remember to keep guests out of the Brown House and other restricted areas during the festivities.

DESC: 21st  I bumped into some travelers on the road and they were tucking into a giant fried turkey leg. It was so bizarre. I'd never imagined that those creatures could grow so large.    The travelers told me that the turkeys are feral and not to be trusted but they make for a great supper, if you can catch one.    I must find these creatures and study them: they'll make a great addition to my book.  [pagebreak]  24th  Today I saw a nye of pheasants gathered around a rather strange and large nest. I intended to take a closer look at these nests to see what they are made up of.  [pagebreak]  25th   Brilliant day! Today I saw one of the aforementioned turkeys in one of the nests! These turkeys are marvelous creatures, but just as feral as the travelers described.  [pagebreak]  27th  God damn, I just saw one eat a Mole Rat!    They were just nesting as per usual, then one of them Moles popped out of the ground and in a flash, one snatched it with its claw!    It then began to shred the creature with it's razor sharp beak, throwing pieces into the air and swallowing them whole. This is far from what I'd expect from any bird none-the-less the turkey!  [pagebreak]  28th  I feel I must approach with caution, these creatures are dangerous, perhaps they are even plotting against me! Last night I could have sworn I heard them stalking around my camp.    Those turkeys are up to something...

<font face='$HandwrittenFont''>My frustrations with Father, and Oberlin for that matter, are getting so bad that it is starting to affect my work.    I understand that they are doing their best to run this Vault and that they have a lot resting on their shoulders, but so do I, so do all of us!  [pagebreak]  Father is a businessman, NOT a scientist, so why does he keep meddling in things he doesn't understand, like that damned Weather Machine!  [pagebreak]  I know that Oberlin has his suspicions about Father, but I'm not sure if I completely trust his judgments either; who's to say he'd run things any differently, or be any less controlling of me than Father is?    I just don't know who to trust anymore...

Day 1 - New land!    I can't believe we've never tried to come down here before. There's a lookout on a hill that would make a great base! Loads of space to take over.    [pagebreak]   Day 2 - New prey!    Scouts saw a guy just waltzing into our tower like he owned the place, (maybe he does but not for long) HA! If it's just the one guy I might give em a fighting chance. Give him some time to hide before I send my guys down there to take over.     [pagebreak]   Day 3 - Dead meat!    We found that sucker up in the tower, the guys caught him off guard recordin somethin and gave em a few new holes before I got there. We might not have got much entertainment from him, but we could've got some info. He was a Ghoul, but had a Vault 63 jumpsuit. Never seen that before. We could've got him to tell us what was in there.     Just in case, I listened to his holotape. I don't know who this Oberlin guy he was leavin the message for is, but sounds like he's being royally screwed over. Hahaha!
The crew killed a Ghoul up in the tower, and they're gonna use bits of him for decoration. I'm gonna see if I can take what's left. Don't think I've had Ghoul before. Wonder if it tastes dry aged?

Blessed be, the Holy Mothman!  Praise unto the Prophet Alex!    Let His divine buzzing guide us through the darkness of this New World! Let her divine guidance show us to the Light that will call him.    My brothers and sisters, we find ourselves far from the Holy Land, far into these untamed lands. Deep into these dark tunnels.  [pagebreak]  Yes, I know, our home is far from us but do not let that weaken your resolve! The Prophet Alex has shown us a flame to kindle our spirit, to draw his embrace. We suffer down here in pursuit of her guidance!  [pagebreak]  Remember, that when your heart bleeds with sorrow, you bleed for Him! This is but a new chapter in our journey, as His children it is our duty to spread his word across the land! To create the Light that will signal unto him a land ready for his dusty shadow.  [pagebreak]  Follow Prophet Alex's Light!  Pray with me now, my mothling siblings!  Praise be, His elegant fuzz!  We offer this to you!   Our blood for you. THEIR blood for you!    Blessed be, the Holy Mothman!

Looks like someone was using this place as a dumping ground. They might be hiding something valuable in there. Take Janine and go check if there's anything good still left. Don't worry about the radiation, you'll be fine if you're quick enough.

Been walking for days and Miles is getting on everyone's nerves. The guy just doesn't know when to let things go, I swear. There'll be more food to scavenge at the next place, not like it's our fault he dropped his supplies when those dogs chased us back there.    If anything he should be thanking Rebecca for taking the blasted things out...    To be expected I suppose, we're all on edge since we set foot in Shenandoah with that freaky storm looming at the center.    Craig keeps pushing us toward that manor just under the eye of the storm, but I got a bad feeling about this...    It's bad juju is all I'm saying.

<font face='$HandwrittenFont' size='17'>  "My name is Ozymandias, King of Kings;  Look on my Works, ye Mighty, and despair!  Nothing beside remains. Round the decay  Of that colossal Wreck, boundless and bare  The lone and level sands stretch far away."

<font face='$HandwrittenFont' size='14'>  My name's Harry Edwards, and if you're reading this, odds are I am dead. Soon after the bombs rained down on us, my dear wife took a turn for the worse, and, well, she's in a better place now. This left me with nothing but a hole in my heart & endless grief, my only lifeline left in this world was my stepson, Thomas.    The issue is that Thomas was off on a trip with his camping group when the bombs came down. I've been tirelessly making my way down to Shenandoah Park for god knows how many weeks now, unsure if my boy is still alive. I keep pushing forward, fueled by a hope that he's out there, safe and sound.  [pagebreak]  The journey's been far from safe, and I'm worried I won't make it to the end. If you're reading this then my worst fears have probably come true. I've failed my son, I couldn't save my wife, and now I am dead.     I have no right to ask, but I beg of you from the bottom of my heart, if you know what it means to be a parent and to love them so deeply your own life means nothing in comparison to theirs. Help Ease the regret off this dead man's shoulders and head to the campground for me. If by some miracle, Thomas is alive, please SAVE MY SON.

With this approach, research could span centuries. Similar to a symbiotic relationship, I could seamlessly attach to a host and move on to a new one when done.

This then in theory could significantly improve cognitive function past its current potential.

What if we could extract memories from a human brain, allowing us to recover lost knowledge and memories from people who have passed on? It would require close teamwork with the engineering lab to devise a method of hooking up a projector to a brain. DESC: December 4th 2080 something or other It's been a while since the bombs dropped, but life in the Vault is still pretty crummy - none of us have completely escaped this radiation malarkey, that's for sure! Perhaps if old Stolz had kept his ego on a leash just for once and built a Vault that was actually finished on time, then we wouldn't be in this damned mess. Instead, he played up to the clock, making this underground palace, and now we're the ones who who have to pay the price. Would it have been so crazy to make sure that we were IN the Vault when the bombs dropped, and not installing some crappy gutters? [pagebreak] March 15th, probably Things ain't improved much and most folks have gotten sick one way or another. But hey, at least we're alive, right? Even if we do look like shriveled raisins, ha! A lotta us have lost our hair and some sad saps have even lost facial features. I ain't so worried about it though; hair or no hair, I'll still be a handsome devil! [pagebreak] April 1st I've got a brilliant idea! Laurence was running his mouth (as usual) about his college days and how many beers he could drink in 10 minutes, well I've challenged him on it - how hard can it be to drink 7 beers in 10 minutes? Since all this weird radiation stuff I probably won't even feel it, right? [pagebreak] May? These last few days I've been feeling... strange. I keep having outbursts and I'm afraid of lashing out at the others. I'm not sure if it's the effects from this damned radiation or if it's because we've been cooped up here for so long. Either way, I don't want to risk hurting anyone else, so I've asked Margaret and the others to lock me in my room. Permanently.

[pagebreak]  I swear I can only hear myself think when I write with all the crazy talk these guys mutter.

<font face='$HandwrittenFont'><font size='16'>Hello, revelers!    We all have a great time with Fasnacht - dressing up, the parades, the bonfires, all the festivities. Everybody loves a good masquerade, right? But one person's unwanted mask is another person's favorite! With that in mind, I've left this basket here for one and all.    You can leave your spare Fasnacht masks here when you don't want 'em, or have a root around and see if somebody's left behind one you've been looking for. The best party is one where everybody's having fun!    Happy Fasnacht,  Your Masked Pal

<font face='$HandwrittenFont' size='18'>< align='left'>It all started while chatting with some fellas in the crew I was running with.     None of us were really feeling the Raider lifestyle, so we broke out some drinks, got to talking about the past. About the park. Apparently, they used to have homes down here, a few years before the bombs fell. They told me about who stole it all from them. Left them all for dead.    None other than the man himself: Stolz.   [pagebreak]  We started scheming right there. One guy said he used to be in with this group of cultists. Said they were damn near unstoppable if they had a goal. We just needed to figure out what kind of flame would draw in their Mothy gaze... Because they believe in a giant holy moth - I didn't mention that yet.    Going to loot the local bookstore. See if I can read up a bit on this local legend. My new buddy thinks I've got a way with words, that I might be able to convince them that I'm some sort of heaven-sent prophet.  [pagebreak]  I know the light at the end of my tunnel: Turning that damn mansion into Hugo's funeral pyre, and Audrey's bright beaming face as I rescue her.     Now I just need them to follow me there. Praise the moth guy!

<font face='$HandwrittenFont' size='18'>< align='left'>I miss her so dearly. I've always hated people, but I loved her. And being out here all by myself... well I never felt more lonely.    I wonder if Audrey would still be attracted to me after my change... I'm looking pretty grim these days. Wouldn't blame her if she'd think of me as a monster... I wonder if she changed like this too?    I can't survive alone out here. Need to move on. Need to plan for how I'm going to get her back. To ruin him and get her back.
<font face='$HandwrittenFont' size='15'>    APPALACHIAN BLOOD MAKES THE TREES GROW, GROW, GROW...    </font>
<font face='$HandwrittenFont' size='15'>    Break the rules and die, BREAK THE RULES AND DIE... Moe must protect the park, Moe must endure, MOE DIGS SAFETY...     </font>

<font face='$HandwrittenFont' size='15'>    The other voice grows louder AND LOUDER... It won't let me go. I can't stop it... YOU DON'T WANT TO STOP IT. I feel it taking over as I write, AND IT FEELS GOOD.  I won't be me anymore... YOU WILL BE BETTER.    </font>
To be placed in storage until Cassidy begins to feel like her old self again.  -Hugo

DESC:
*** IMPORTANT ORDERS *** Good News Everyone! I'm pleased to inform you that we will once again be hosting this year's Shenandoah Halloween Spooktacular. Now, as you all know, I LOVE Halloween and therefore it's our duty to transform Rapidan Camp into something wonderful for this special occasion. This will be even more important given all the new friends returning to the park. While I, of course, expect the grounds to be in tip-top condition, it's also essential that the decorations adhere to the "extra spooky" guidelines that I've outlined in years past. !Please do not skimp on the ghastly details!

Oh, I would hate if we were a laughing stock this year! My colleague Hemsworth, over at Stolz's residence, would surely love it if we were to embarrass ourselves. Then again, he can't talk, not with his tacky garden in such complete chaos. Oh sorry, I seem to have gone on a tangent again. Returning to the matter at hand... Make sure you pose the skeletons nicely: I insist that each one meets a level of "exhaling-through-the-nostrils" caliber of comedy for our guests. And please do NOT forget the candy bowls again this year. Lastly, ensure all guests remain off the lawns and floral arrangements, lest they damage the fLoWeRs! Now, let's get to work, shall we? Grounds Supervisor, Gumley.

DESC: <font face='$HandwrittenFont' size='16'>Magellan,    This definitely feels like the coward's way out, you know, writing it all down instead of saying it to your face. But frankly, I don't think you've got enough sense left for us to have a reasonable discussion about this.    I'm just going to give it to you straight. This is my letter of resignation. Look, we've had some good times, and...well, mostly bad times. Truth is, I've been the strongarm for more caravans than I can count, and I've never bailed on a job once. This is my exception.    For your own good, PLEASE, and I mean PLEASE give up on this "training the Overgrown" idea. They're frothing at the mouth in their cages, waiting to rip our faces off and saute them.     Have you ever heard of a sunk cost fallacy? The whole idea that sometimes, when people sink an immense amount of time, effort, or even money into something, they have to see it all the way through even when it's failing miserably. Yeah, I think you've got that. Your "cost" has sunk to the Mariana Trench at this point.    Just give it up, man. Go back to Atlantic City. You were conned. We all were.    -Rick</font>

<font face='$HandwrittenFont' size='18'>SAL!!! YOU SLIMEY, NO GOOD, TWO-TIMING, THESPIAN-SABOTAGING BASTARD!    I staked my whole livelihood in this venture! Every single cap I earned busking on the Boardwalk, all the blood, sweat, and tears (especially blood) that I shed working the games for Charlotte. All of that, wasted!    That "scientist" you told me to talk to? Well, I went to the address you gave me, and guess what? There's no such thing as the All-American Institute of Botanical Humanoid Research. Just a bunch of louts squatting in an abandoned building! I'm seriously starting to doubt that the Overgrown can be trained at all.     Damn it all! I won't let some charlatan pull the wool over my eyes! As the Bard once wrote, you scullion! You rampallian! You fustiliarian! I'll tickle your catastrophe!    I shall honor my namesake's legacy and use his navigational talents to find my own way in this business!    Most unsincerely not yours,    Magellan</font>

<font face='$HandwrittenFont' size='14'>Monday:    -Basic words and phrases    -Juggling (balls, not knives, they definitely are not ready for that)    -Breathing techniques    Tuesday:    -Cognitive behavioral therapy    -Hula hoops    -Table manners    Wednesday:    -Painting by numbers    -Singing by scale    -Tap dancing    Thursday:    -Poetry    -Trapezing    -Ballet dancing    Friday:    -Calisthenics    -Sword swallowing (starting with sticks)    -Balance training    Saturday:    -Rest Day    Sunday:    -Fencing    -Strength training    -Acrobatics</font>

<font face='$Typewriter_Font' size='18'>Magellan,    Let's keep this on the down low, huh? My uncle'd blow a gasket if he knew I was selling to some damn troubadour so far off from our main trade routes, but I can try to write it off as a trade with Mayor Tim. He won't know any better so long as I just put "Atlantic City" on the order invoice.    Despite the obvious secrecy, I wanted to have our little deal in writing. Here it is, all itemized and whatnot:    Wooden wagon (1): 1500 caps    Live brahmin (3): 2500 caps    Temp security contractors (3): 3000 caps    All in all, you owe me a good 7,000 caps to be paid up front. I don't know how much you make juggling swords or whatever it is you do, but frankly, I don't care so long as I get paid.    I don't have the metal livestock cages you asked for. Not sure where to send you for those. If you're already in Atlantic City, you might want to try the Lombardi Family. They typically have reason for uh, such things.    I hope whatever business venture you've got going on pans out.    Sincerely,    -Luca Costa</font>

Date: September, 2105. We have garnered fantastic results from our latest expedition into the region. Though still dangerous, I believe that a return to caravan trading on Skyline Drive will have a high value. Despite the expedition itself going well, we encountered the remains of Axel's parents. I'll look after their belongings till their young one is a bit older. Hopefully he'll understand. No need to crush his hopes, though, we all need something to keep us going. Till then, I'll keep up his training.

Dear prospective merchant, This contract will outline the terms of your collaboration with Milepost Zero, a branch of the Blue Ridge Caravan Company. A starter package will be available for purchase from your operations manager. Further benefits of working for Milepost Zero are stated below: - Exclusive access to Milepost Zero and (in limited capacities) BRC Co. suppliers. - Exclusive stables for care of your Brahmin, under expert management of a stable master. - Rights to open a stall within a Milepost Zero marketplace. - Lodging accommodations and 2 meals a day at cost value. Along with these benefits, your caravan will be assigned a guard in exchange for a commission fee. In signing this contract, you agree to uphold the name and brand of Milepost Zero and its affiliate the Blue Ridge Caravan Company. You agree to pay all upkeep fees in full at the end of each month. In the event of your untimely demise, your next of kin will be given one month after the time of your death to retrieve your personal belongings, or they will be forfeited to Milepost Zero. As a representative of the company, you are prohibited from trading with outside suppliers. Goods obtained through illegitimate business will result in a forfeit of this contract and said goods remaining within the possession of Milepost Zero. We look forward to years of success together! Signature:

<font face='$76HandwrittenNeat_Font' size='20'>  Theodore,    If you're reading this... If you're even still alive, I've rejoined Blue Ridge. That's right, they're still kicking.    I don't know what happened or why you never came back. I'm sure you had your reasons, and I need to do what's best for Marley. She has your eyes, and your stubbornness. I wish you could have seen her grow into the strong woman she is today. I know you would have been so proud. I'm sure you'll have as many questions as do I, hopefully in time they can all be answered.    If this letter ever reaches you, we've traveled to the new BRC Co. headquarters at the Big Bend Tunnel. Please be careful, the world is not the same as it was.    I love you, always.  </font>

<font face='$76HandwrittenNeat_Font' size='20'>  Ineke!    I have a special request for you. Have you heard of "hanbok?" It's a garb worn by the people of Joseon (that's the old word for Korea, I think!).     My grandfather had a very nice one he wore every chuseok (that's our Thanksgiving!)     It's fallen into disrepair, but do you happen to have any similar fabric? Do you sew? Can you fix it for me? I will pay you in a variety of very pretty Cryptid bones.    Actually, do you think you could attach those to the outfit in some way?    Anyway, thanks in advance!    - Windy  </font>

DESC: <font face='$76HandwrittenNeat_Font' size='20'>Ain't got no time for plezentrees. I almost died! We was having a peaceful rest, and suddenly I hear some rustling. Ryan gets up and starts hollering. "Raiders!" But these weren't no raiders. They was scary as the dead of night. They looked all burnt up. They moved quicker than a mountain lion. And I swear their eyes was gleeming red.    I got shot and I need to go get help. I thought I should write this first in case I don't make it. Then whoever finds me can get a warning. Maybe I'll talk on the radio too. Timmy taut me how to do it. Poor Timmy is dead now but I can still use what he taut me. Thanks, Timmy.  [pagebreak]  Dear Diary,    Everything is ok now. Well half the things are ok. Turns out I didn't get shot too bad after all. But I am dying anyways. After all that work at Emmett Mountain, the radeeation went in my blood and Doc says its killing me from the inside out. I think I'm too sad to write any more right now.  [pagebreak]  Dear Diary,    I think things might be ok soon. We found a radeeation special doctor, and they are actually the same people who shot me. I know that sounds bad but it may not be so bad. They are trying to help now. People sure is complex.    The thing is that I may not be the same the next time I write. I'm not too sure about it yet. I just hope people won't be afraid of me.    Love, Leamon  [pagebreak]  Dear Diary,    I woke up and I'm a ghool! These were the changes I was talking about. Miss Par-thee-nee-a said this was the only way to cure my irradatied-ness. I was scared to do it but not anymore.    My skin feels all funny and it sure is odd not having a nose. But I think I can get used to it. I should ask Parthina how to spell her name. Most people here are kind of scary but she is nice.    Well that's all for today. I think my life is going to be pretty diffrent from now on.

Hey Kev,    Don't strain yourself on my behalf. Writing more than a couple sentences is practically a marriage vow for you.    And... I'm not being facetious when I say that. It's been good getting your letters. I know they don't come easily to you. So thanks.    You and Maddox and the crew... You aren't wrong for seeking safety. The privilege of getting to live without a target on your back -- of course anyone would want that. I want that. And I'm telling you that I have it, as much as anyone living in this wild Wasteland has it.    Haven't I proven that living with smoothskins is possible? Sure, it's not perfect. It gets tiring having to explain yourself again and again. But between tiring, and completely cut off from the outside world? I'll take option one, please.    I don't know why I'm bothering to say all this. I know it won't change your mind. And that's okay, really. It makes you who you are. Guess I just wish it were possible for both of us to have our way. And everyone there to live their lives to the fullest, whatever that means for them.    Thanks for taking care of everyone, Kev. Just remember to take care of yourself, too.    Eugenie

Jaye,    Haven't heard from you in a bit, so I wanted to drop a line. I hope you're still concocting new styles like the best of them. Some of the ghouls over there could really use your advice. I know they don't go out much, but what about sparing the eyes of their own crew?    Jokes aside, I hope you're alright. You're good at dressing yourself up, and that means the inside too. But you should know that everyone is there for you, not just me. I wish I could still be there, too, but you know why I had to go. And I hope you're not holding it against me.    Guess for now I'll just offer a reminder that you're okay how you are. That what happened to you wasn't your fault, just as it wasn't for the rest of us. Except Parthenia, I guess. And anyone who truly loves you wouldn't hold it against you.     Go back to your family, one day. Let them see what you've become. Who you've become. See what happens. And if they're not proud... Well, you'll know then that they're not a worth damn anymore.    Eugenie

<font face='$76HandwrittenNeat_Font' size='16'>Maddox - Exemplary. Helped mentor others.    Luke - Good improvement.    Jaye - Good improvement. Complained about shoulder bruises. Recommended padding.    Connor - Average.    Madison - Average.    Lilac - Subpar, needs additional training.    Debbie - Arrived late, hit every target in record time. Chastised for excessive personal conversations.    Ernie - Absent. Maddox requested exemption on his behalf. Will broach subject again on later date.    Parthenia - Absent for 3rd time this month. Probably lost track of time again. Too dangerous to send someone to the lab for her. Need other solution.

<font size='18'>When I was a girl, the world was mine.     The sun burned strong with the warmth of dawn. The stars shone bright with dreams. My heart burned with a love for life and all its possibilities.    So I kept asking myself, out of everything that could happen, why did possibility raze the world I loved? Why did it rot my flesh and blight my insides? Why did it leave me so pitifully alone, so desperately seeking a kindred spirit? Why did it open my eyes to those destitute dregs of humanity whom I had never truly looked upon before?    Why did possibility bless me with life while others perished? Why did it open my arms to those beautiful souls whose redemption would become my life's purpose? Why did it grant me a new perspective, a new lens through which to admire this imperfect, beautiful world?    Why would we ever do anything less than shout gratitude into the winds by living, by loving, by dreaming, and never, ever giving up on each other?    The world I love isn't somewhere in the distant future. It's here, now. The sun still burns with the warmth of dawn. The stars still shine bright with dreams. You only have to look up and be willing to see them.    When I was a girl, the world was mine. I only lost it because I let go of it. Now, with all of you, I'm grabbing on again. And there's more possibility than ever before.
