FULL: To whoever else was an idiot
DESC: Joy Lynn told me that hunting down that old treasure wouldn't be a good idea, and I guess she'd be laughing if she knew. I'm sure she could probably figure it out from my disappearance, but for all she knows, I got strung up by some raiders. It'd be less embarrassing honestly.    Grandpa used to tell stories about this treasure from the 1950's or something, and lone behold it's real. He mentioned Coopers and Bulls from his research, but turns out it was the old blue Bullengrube Hole. It was easy enough to sink down with that rock, but no way I could hold my breath long enough to swim back up.     I ask you stranger, if you've got the gall to swim back out, and it's still around the 2090's, tell Joy Lynn you saw Leroy go down defending a family from some raiders.

DESC: Notice to all employees: As of 12:00 am tomorrow, ownership of this facility will officially transfer from Atomic Mining Services, Ltd. to Raven Financial Holdings LLC. The company will close the mine with immediate effect and liquidate its assets. All personnel are to report to management today at 4:00 pm for reassignment. Look folks... I know it's harsh, but we saw the writing on the wall ages ago. The coal's run dry and you'll be put on veins that can feed your family. Here's to new beginnings. - Marc

One last check of supplies before sealing this place off. Once we commit to collapsing the tunnels, there will be no turning back -- we will remain here until we complete our experiments and the Enclave returns for the results. This new lab, equipped with state-of-the-art hydroponics technology sourced from partners at Vault-Tec, is well positioned to survive for many decades in complete secrecy -- the perfect setting for uninterrupted work on one of the most consequential projects in history! It may be intimidating, but I still believe aligning ourselves with the Enclave is a worthwhile cause. In studying Ultracite, we have the opportunity to revolutionize energy in a world racked by resource wars. A full understanding of this material has the potential to better the lives not just of millions of Americans, but of everyone around the globe. So check and double check your equipment. Make sure everything is in place. Get ready to make history. Robert Gaines, PhD

Marc, it's Hanley. What the hell is Raven LLC, and what do they want with our mine? Why would they buy us out just to close us? It don't make sense! I thought AMS protected its techs, or I'd never have taken this job. This company's gone off the deep end! We're already a dozen bots per person. Soon there'll be none of us left! You say we'll be transferred to Welch, but that's cold comfort. As soon as we get there, we'll see another round of cuts and then we'll be out in the streets while those robots have our jobs. You mark my words, Marc! Nobody is safe. Nobody!

Team, As construction continues on the new research laboratory, it is of the utmost importance that we maintain the strictest possible security measures. The Enclave will make sure of that. Any and all intruders are to be disposed of immediately. Shoot first, no questions will be asked. Word of this lab's existence must never reach the local population. A lot is riding on you as security officers, but as you've no doubt noticed we will be getting backup soon in the EN06 Guardian, our new sentry robot. With it in place, our role will turn inwards -- to the lab's new residents. I trust you are and will remain up to the job. The future of America, after all, rests on your shoulders. Captain John Holloway

Word of warning: Robert's favorite pet is on the loose. Not sure how it got out, but please be very careful, as it's no harmless garter snake. One bite from that thing could put you in the ER for a week. So, caution.

Sensors in the surrounding tunnels have detected motion and sound reminiscent of human -- or human-sized -- activity for the first time in our many years underground. Epsilon Squad has been dispatched to investigate, but as an added precaution our technicians have installed an automated lockdown protocol that will initiate at the first sign of foreign incursion. Recognize that only the voice print of top management can override this procedure. That means that in most scenarios, intruders must be dealt with before the lockdown will lift. There can be no compromise on the sanctity of this facility. You have been warned.

Looking on the great subterranean lake stretching out before me at the heart of these caverns, I can't help but think: what a wonder, this combination of nature and mankind! There are those who would say we spoiled the natural beauty of it all, but the verdant color of this Ultracite really does call to me in a way I've never felt before. It's like its secrets are reaching out, waiting to be uncovered. I can't wait to get to work! Beyond its visual allure, this cavern is the perfect epicenter for our studies. The Enclave, for all its faults, really did outdo itself in that regard. The heart of the miners' atomic charge beats with its energy. Ultracite is positively everywhere! Plenty for us to study in its 'natural' habitat as well as bring into the lab for further experimentation. Yes, I can already see that this alliance of convenience -- between the Enclave and my research staff -- is primed to pay real dividends for the benefit of mankind. Where once there was doubt, now there is conviction. Let's get to work! Robert Gaines, PhD

FULL: Today is not the last day I can write
DESC: Today is not the last day I can write.    Today is not the last day I can write.    Today is not the last day I can write.    Tday na nnot wrt.    Tdn wrt

If you're reading this you probably know that you're going feral. And you likely don't have much time, but how you face the twilight is your decision. Nobody is going to make you stay.    This place is a sanctuary for our kind. Hang on as long as you can, but when it's time to let go, travel through the Last Door. Nobody will hurt you in there.     Use the grounds, treat your fellow residents kindly, and take the time you need to make your peace.     - Maddox
You don't have to go in before you're ready but when you are LOCK the door behind you and TOSS the key out BEFORE you open the inner door.    No loud noises, please.
Barbara, I love you. I know we won't remember each other but at least we'll be together here. Forever.     Johnny

<font face='$Typewriter_Font' size='16'>I insisted Hetty take a term off from the university so she could get away from the stress of teaching, but she's been increasingly paranoid, and insists we were followed. Apparently one of her students is a real nutcase and gives her the creeps, but I've assured her she's being ridiculous. There would be no reason for someone to follow us all the way out here.     It's only day 3, and she's been frantic, claiming she keeps seeing this guy lurking around outside. At this point, I think it would have been better to check her into Allegheny for a bit because I'm starting to go a bit crazy dealing with her. I needed this time for myself and my own work, too.  </font>

<font face='$HandwrittenFont' size='18'>I haven't had this much fun in ages, my blood is rushing!  I followed Professor Danielson when I heard that she was going on vacation, and to my luck, it was out in the middle of nowhere! I couldn't stand going a full term without her.     After a few days, her ignoramus husband went out to the shack, and I had the perfect opportunity to introduce myself. Professor Danielson wasn't as grateful as I had hoped when she saw me kill that ass of a man, and unfortunately I had to end her as well. I had planned to cook her a wonderful meal of her ungrateful husband, but now I've got to preserve the both of them to make the meat last longer. Their heads do sit quite nicely on the mantel though.    I think I'll remain here for a while, as it seems the perfect place to indulge in my superior preferences of food without being disturbed.

<font face='$HandwrittenFont' size='18'>I was making my bi-weekly trip to the Mega Stop this morning, and everything seemed off. It was peculiar that there were so many abandoned cars, and the Mega Stop was trashed and desolate. Normally, I have no trouble finding someone to sneak into the trunk, but it took an unacceptable amount of time to find someone that didn't run off when I came close. Something catastrophic must have happened. This is really going to screw up my system.

Justin took the Last Door yesterday and we're all going to miss his cooking. He said he was a chef before the war. A chef in Austin, Texas. Austin is the capital of Texas and I am Sarah from Charleston. Charleston is the capital of West Virginia. I am trying my best to remember all of the capitals of all of the states and it is getting harder every day.   Justin forgot that Austin was a capital. As long as I can remember that Charleston is the capital and that every state has a capital and I can name those capitals then I can remember that my name is Sarah and I won't need to go through the door yet.   Sarah

Write your name here if you're going through the Last Door.     If you see someone forget, please write their name for them.    Ryan Morgan  Deandra Gillis  "Lefty"  Justin Tailor  John Marchette  Barbara Marchette  Cleo Jeffries  Morris Boone  Sarah Lopez  Ricky (we never got his last name)

DESC: <font face='$76HandwrittenNeat_Font' size='16'>Point Repose has become quite the curious anomaly. The state of Radiant Hills is dismal and dead, while Repose has flourished, and even begun to sprout out-of-climate fauna. I'd assumed that birds had carried seeds over, however the substantial growth is what's fascinated me! I've made trips over to the area to collect soil samples, and it's just as I had guessed. The soil over here at the camp is far more basic, while the soil at Repose is acidic, likely due to the CO2 from the decomposing ferals. This means that rapid radiation-based growth might act a bit like a hydrangea, which changes the color of its petals depending on the pH of the soil.     Another factor to consider is the distinction between the tenure of the radioactive material at the silo versus the materials' comparatively brief use at Repose. Here, the barrels had likely sat for decades --irradiating everything over time. However, for their new location, I don't know its long scale effects yet. We could possibly watch this new forest decay away in the coming years. Perhaps I could talk Asher into bringing me some jars of soil the next time they scavenge out in the Toxic Valley and Cranberry Bog. I don't want to sacrifice the little soil I have in the planters for testing.

DESC: <font face='$HandwrittenFont' size='15'>           My dearest Rose,    I have wandered through my life feeling numb, resigning myself to fleeting and shallow forms of happiness. Then one fateful day, you entered my life and rekindled the joy I thought was lost forever inside the dark abyss of my soul. A mere flutter of your Atlantic eyes or your heavenly smile greeting me at the bedroom door had the uncontrollable power to magnetize happiness back into my very core.    You and I are well aware, my dear, that I've lived a hard life. I thought I understood loss, that I and it were even one and the same, but I came to understand that true loss is knowing you hold something more precious than life itself. For me, that's you, and it's always been you. It will be you, forevermore. The thought of losing you forever makes my life feel incomplete and hollow. It's simply no life at all if you're not by my side.    You're engaged to another man, yet you cannot deny that our pasts still haunt us. Yet this is my last chance to win your heart. I don't intend to just keel over and accept this fate. For once in my life, I choose to fight for our future. If your heart still yearns for me, as mine does for you, meet me at our special spot by the pond at 10 PM on Friday. Should you decide not to come, I will accept your answer and will honor your wishes, leaving your life forever.    Yours Eternally,  Patrick

<font face='$HandwrittenFont'>Entry 1:  Sold most of our catches for far cheaper than we ought this month, but I just can't bear to see the state of the poor souls that we meet in the ports. Least this way they can fill their bellies for a night. The men think I've gone soft, but they're forgetting how easy we've got it.  [pagebreak]  Entry 2:  Spied some almighty shadows beneath the ship of late. These waters grow more treacherous with every passing day. If it's not the sea herself, it's the creatures within.  [pagebreak]  Entry 3:  Blessed Poseidon, have mercy on our wretched souls! This storm has raged at us for three days and nights. It didn't give us the faintest warning of its coming, neither. She better blow over soon, for Linda-Lee can't take much more of this abuse.   </f>

<font face='$HandwrittenFont'>Entry 4:   I feel I must be dreaming. I've woken up ashore? God knows how. Flashes of terrible visions plague my mind. I'll be damned if I can tell whether they're nightmares or memories, though. Same figure always lurking in them. It's hard to know what's real or not anymore, especially now I'm plagued with these strange urges.      Entry 5  Been following them for so long now, doing all kinds of strange things. Anything to stop the pain.     Find myself in agony often, or is it ecstasy?   </f>

Anglers Wanted!

No experience required, just a strong arm, a willing mind and some entrepreneurial spirit.

Come find us at Fisherman's Rest in the Mire.

Brothers and Sisters,

With the repairing of the bridge complete, the time has come for us to begin our expansion into the west. We move into the unknown in order to expand our sacred lands, but with the winged one watching over us, we shall prevail. If any of us shall fall, find comfort in knowing that the wise and holy Mothman shall shepherd them to the divine light.

That's why they've begun the inanimate operation! If it has eyes, there's a good chance they're watching. Watch them before they watch you!        Keep an eye out for anything with a face that's somewhere it shouldn't be.  The only thing I know is safe is my Lil' Ginger Snuggles. But that's only because I dissected him 4 times to be sure.

Employee Notice Dilapidated Rooms ------------------------------------------------ Hey, everyone, we've been made aware that a number of buildings around the fort are unsafe for customers. We cannot afford to repair all the buildings, which leads us to a new strategy we're going to trial: When customers arrive at the fort and receive their costumes, we will put them to work! Tell them that troops would be tasked with carrying out repairs on the fort during downtime. They get to live out their fantasies of being a soldier, we get free repairs. It is a win-win situation. Just make sure all equipment is returned before they leave; we don't need any extra costs right now. If you have a problem with the trial strategy, you can hand in your resignation. Thanks, team! Stay awesome! Phil, Joe, and Susie P.S. This is NOT to be spoken about outside of work or with any non-employees.

Employee Notice Damaged Outfits ------------------------------ From now on, we will be taking deposits from visitors for the equipment they're wearing. A lot of our costumes already have holes in them so we need to start cracking down. Also, brush up on your sewing skills during downtime - we need someone to patch these costumes up!

This could actually be a good additional job for visitors; we'll look into this as an option. Phil

Susie, Things aren't looking good on our accounts. We can talk about it later, but for now I've renewed the insurance for this place. It is good to know we'd be able to recoup our losses in the event of a tragic accident or disaster. Really good to know. Phil

<font face='$HandwrittenFont' size ='18'>  05/22  I can't believe Mad Bill Barlow survived all this time. Even crazier, all the places across America to go, and he came back to this dump?     Guess he remembered the stash was here... Just like old times. Wonder why we were drawn to this place? Maybe it's fate.    [pagebreak]  06/13  Bill took charge and everyone started gettin' their shit together.     Says its survival of the fittest now and he's gonna fight for our place in Ohio under the Rust King.     Says as long as we do what he needs and pay tribute to the guy, we get to live how we want out here.    [pagebreak]  09/30  Captured some of those Feral Ghouls. Apparently the Rust King uses them in his arena sometimes, must be good playthings for the Deathclaws he likes to keep.     Been selling one or two on the side to some weirdos who live at the old diner down the way.     Don't care what they're doing with 'em long as we get our cut. Might take a trip to Highway Town later, take a load off.    [pagebreak]  10/02  Got attacked by a pack of ghouls moving down from Athens. Managed to kill 'em all, but they broke a bunch of our defenses, and we lost a couple guys.    Bill had us pulling all kind of things apart to try to get the barriers up again. What a pain.     If I didn't know better I'd say they attacked us to get the ones we captured back... Can those things even think?    [pagebreak]  10/04  They came outta nowhere! Radscorpions. Right from under our feet! Didn't think they could break through concrete like that.    We didn't stand a chance. Dunno what happened to everyone, saw a couple die after we scattered.    I got stung pretty bad, managed to lock myself in secure storage, but it's still trying to get me. The bigger they are, the weaker the poison... right?

We thought there would only be a few of them... then when we opened the door, we got swarmed. They got Mike and Jerry. It was chaos. Sarah and I ran to try and escape as soon as them two got mauled. Last I saw, she was running along the platform followed by a group of those things. I climbed up here to get away from them, which seemed like a good plan at first but I ain't got no food or water. It looks like these ferals aren't gonna let up. They've been circling below for days.

Dammit. We should have waited for the others to come back before trying anything. They're not even back yet, something could have went wrong for them too. At this point, it feels hopeless and I'm running out of options. I'm not sure what to do.

<font face='$Terminal_Font' size='12'>Foreman Jacobs,    Just writing to update you on the progress of our automated repair robots. We're happy to report that, as of their most recent tests, they are now performing on par with our best human workers. With this success, our plans are now to roll out full automation within the next six months at your facility. As a result of this fantastic opportunity, we are regrettably going to have to dismiss a number of the human workers at your location. To ensure the robots continue to operate at peak efficiency, we wish to retain you and an engineer of your recommendation as maintenance workers. Training will be provided to ensure you are both able to do what is required.    With regards to the other workers at the facility, please notify them of their dismissal at the earliest opportunity. In acknowledgment of the stress and upset this may cause, we are offering a special severance package of two weeks pay, and a coupon for a meal at the Corner House Cafe in Athens. You may consult the information pack we have provided for more details.    ---------------  Linda Montgomery  Automation Director  Heartland & Eastern Rail

It seems like things are on the up for us! We stopped by Highway Town today to sell the junk we managed to scavenge over the last few days. While we were there, Brett got word of an abandoned railroad service workshop not too far away, so we followed the train track south to see if it'd be a good place to setup a more permanent base. We arrived about an hour ago. It's looking to be a really good option. It's strange that it hasn't been occupied already! There's lots of buildings in good condition and open train cars that we could make into actual livable spaces! There's only one issue really, the main workshop building is locked up and looks like it's set up to warn people away. Not to mention, there's also some pretty strange sounds coming from inside...

<font face='$76HandwrittenNeat_Font' size='20'>I've been seeing more and more people falling ill lately. It starts with a cough that grows heavier with time, your mouth starts to dry up, and then the thirst hits. A thirst that's sent some people crazy. I saw one man kill another, all because he took too long filling his canteen.

<font face='$HandwrittenFont' size='20'>I've had another two sacks of Brahmin feed stolen - the town folk must be getting desperate if they want to eat that shit. We're gonna have to buy double when the traders return. Hungry Brahmin are difficult to work with as it is, and the dead ones ain't lifting a thing.

Someone needs to do something about the Rust King's men! It's the third time this week I've had to repair the turbines cause they keep taking shots at them. Parts ain't cheap! If they keep this up, the town's gonna end up with no power.

<font face='$HandwrittenFont' size='16'>The Super Duper Mart has been quiet for a few days; there's been no signs of life from the Rust King's Army. Is something brewing? We should be on high alert in case of an attack, and maybe send some scouts to take a closer look.    No matter what we do, we need to avoid the pass to the south. Nigel said he saw a group of raiders setting up in the old diner, and that can only mean trouble. I gotta say though, whatever they're cooking down there smells damn delicious. That scent has got me hungrier than a Yao Guai.

Jessica's Diary: Entry #17 6/27/2090 I'm sick of hearing how we're gonna make it. Suppose we do set up a food supply and we don't starve. Suppose we don't join this "Rust King." What are we gonna to do about the threat that creeps in at night? One of those scorpions stung Stan's leg. He swelled up and then he died. Another one took half a magazine to run off and it still killed the guy on watch. They come up from underground - seems like they're everywhere. What are we supposed to do when death is right under our feet?

Something's changing around here. You can feel it. We saw another group of raiders heading south yesterday. I'm pretty sure they're the ones who skinned Jack for fun the other week. This time they waved as they were going by didn't fire a shot. Just laughed. People keeping talking about this guy down that way, this "Rust King." They said if you're strong enough you can join him. That you must join him. That's he's something more than a man. I don't know. Maybe we're wasting our time here, scraping by. Might be time we headed south too.

THE PROFESSOR'S LESSONS #12: LIGHT

"Light is the equalizer and the revelator. I harness, I amplify, I discharge. I am the Talos of the new age! Listen! In purest form (4.74 x 10^14 Hz., alternatively ) burst interval lumens reveal honest bone under the unhardened flesh. I will not avert my eyes (50 milliliters MedX, dual ocular administration) from electromagnetic salvation. I gaze into the petawatts, the joules, I rejoice in the boiling of the blood (100 C.) I see myself in the fire. I see you there too! And you! Rejoice for the world and for your place in it. For I ask you, do we not stand in the new world revealed at last by the atom's light?" -Professor Franklin Metter, November 12, 2082, related to Herman the Lesser upon the summit of the Cave of ASH.

<font size='15'>Stan's caterwauling about starvation. Again. Hand-wringing about Wasteland raids that turn up nothing to eat. If the folks they were shaking down had food, then why do they look like skin and bones?    Stan doesn't think. None of them do. Where the others see a parking lot, I see self-sufficiency. It won't happen overnight. I know that. I'm not insane. We need to dig out the area around the ruptured pipe. So, we need tools. (Super-Duper Mart?)    Then what we need to do is round up the strongest fish we can find and dump them in the parking lot.     Soon, a hardy stock will emerge. One born for the parking lot life.

Dear reader, Do you often rummage through others' belongings while they're away? I, the great Mystic Margret, have foreseen your arrival for some time now, hence this note. Should the currents of time bring us together, there is much we are destined to share. You may doubt my mystical abilities, but time will prove me right, as it always does. P.S. Try not to break anything on your way out.

<font face='$HandwrittenFont' size='20'>Tony,  How on earth are we supposed to keep track of anything when this workshop looks like a bomb site?    I've lost two schematic plans that are essential for maintaining the signs. I need them to fix these broken piles of junk for the customers. I had them yesterday and haven't left town, so they have to be here somewhere in all this mess.      Head out as soon as you read this and see if you can find them lying around town while I hold down the fort and search here.     And when you get back, you're cleaning up this mess.

~The Three Little Towns~

A long, long time ago, three minor groups tried to survive in the Wasteland. To do so, each built a settlement. The first faction threw theirs together using old tents and tarps, ignoring the dangers lurking in the shadows. The second used cheap wood and rusted metal, focused on speed & ease. Neither cared much for planning: it was just a place to eat, sleep, and pillage. The third faction, however, worked tirelessly. They built high above the ground, away from the chaos below. With steel beams and solid metal walls, they crafted a fortress built to last. [pagebreak] One day, a ruthless warlord turned his gaze on the two weaker factions. Watching them waste their days in leisure, he thought, "What lovely forts you've built. I think I'll take them for myself." With a group of loyal raiders, he stormed the first town. Within moments, it was torn to shreds - cut fabric, broken tents, and scattered bones. Satisfied, the tyrant moved on to the second faction. Their makeshift walls crumbled easily. Within mere minutes, every last survivor of the onslaught was rounded up under his new rule. But the warlord wasn't done. For power, boredom, or perhaps as a test of strength, he attempted an attack on the fortress in the sky. He charged, expecting another easy win. But no matter how hard he attacked, the stronghold held firm. Hours turned into days. His weapons barely left a mark. [pagebreak] Desperate, he tried forcing his way in through the only entrance: The Elevator. But just as he stepped inside, the town's heroic mechanic shut it down, sending the warlord and his men tumbling back into the Wasteland. For the first time, the big bad man had met his match. Because in the Wasteland, you should always prepare for the worst. (Writters Note: I Need to find a better way to end the story, this wont do)

The End

Howdy, Got some new information for you, straight from the cesspool we call Highway Town. Hope your cap stash is deep, I want no more of that short-changing stuff you tried pulling last time, or we're gonna have a real problem. Info starts on the next page... [pagebreak]

Tip-off's

Info 1: A lone, unarmed traveller, as dumb as rocks stayed for a night or two. He was muttering some stuff about how he was heading toward Athens for a supply run. He mentioned he might camp near the Drive-In along the way, an easy mark for a robbery if there ever was one. Hell, he might even thank you for making his backpack lighter, the fool.

WELCOME TO HIGHWAY TOWN -------------------------------------- Where true freedom reigns, and the right to live and do as you choose is respected and upheld. We have few rules, but one stands above all: Your freedom ends where another's begins. If your actions infringe on the rights of others or disturb the peace, expect the same in return-ranging from jail and expulsion to, in extreme cases, death on sight. Live free, tread wisely, and always remember the golden rule. Signed: Highway Town Enforcement

I got stung good and it burns. God it burns hotter than I ever would have thought. They're all that mound, burrowed in deep. It can't get me up here but that damned bot, it's as bad as the venom. The last thing I hear is going to be corn trivia.     If you read this, stay off that mound.

Dave, Another guest started throwing up yesterday, right by the gate, and just as a family with two kids were walking in. One kid got sick all over their shoes, and it was so embarrassing! I had to let the family play for free as an apology. This guy complained about feeling nauseous around the Suuwassea initially, but mentioned he could smell something odd around all of our dinos. He said it reminded him of the smell around the big Abraxodyne plant. I'm getting a little nervous that he suspects something as I saw him snapping photos. I think we should try to get rid of some barrels before anyone comes digging - quite literally! I'll come back tonight to start shifting some by myself. I'd appreciate your help. Donna.

To all staff,

We need to make sure that Hole 9 is more difficult. I watched a kid score a hole-in-one today, so he got his 'free golf for a year' prize. It may be a great promotion, but it's not good for our profits! Dave.

Donna, Could you send over four more barrels as soon as possible; they work wonders on the weeds around here! Though our flower patch isn't as colorful as it usually is, we're getting used to the vibrant reds.

Chad.

This note details the ritualistic manufacture and consumption of combat-enhancing drugs and discusses the teachings of the Professor in a nigh-ritualistic fashion. From those note we understand that these people are on drugs constantly.

THE PROFESSOR'S LESSONS #2: WIND

"So how, then, are we to supply the power that our arms require? That the soldiers' iron hides demand? How shall we, down to the merest flickers of fusion's light, seize tight our destiny? I have seen it. I have seen it in a dream. We must draw from the tumult of the sky itself. From the universal laws of conflict and struggle. The very atmosphere is awash in violence: clashing thunderheads, waves of pressure, and pitiless gale. A perfect, ceaseless tempest of pascal and millibar, eager for the bit. We will construct machines to harness the wind, to gather and distribute its power. 1009 millibars or lower! Enough to make an anemometer scream!"

-Professor Franklin Metter, July 7, 2081, related to Herman the Lesser upon the summit of the Cave of ASH

THE PROFESSOR'S LESSONS #1: TEMPERING

"When you were cast into this Wasteland you were unfit for survival. Your skin was soft, your eyes shied from the glare of the sun, and the emissions of the killing electromagnetic radiation. You were weak. Not yet tempered. And yet, hope remains: that the untested may yet be tempered. That they may be saved! Hope they may clad themselves in poly-laminate and ablative ceramics, that they may drench their organs in life-enhancing pharmaceuticals! A homecoming, a rebirth! A hope that the untested may prove themselves fit!" - Professor Franklin Metter, April 8, 2080, related to Herman the Lesser in the shadow of the Cave of ASH.

<font size='15'>Maggie,  You asked for a story for your birthday, well, here's one. The day that changed everything.    Herman found him, the man from Athens, the one we'd later call Professor. Nearly shot him on the spot. It was the day everything changed for us. No, I wasn't there, but I heard about it    It was the early days, when Herman and his crew were moving out from West Virginia into Ohio. They hadn't been here before, and we had no people, no ties. They'd hit a small Army depot or something, made off with some supplies, probably left more than a few bodies. Took a good haul.    It wasn't as bad then, but it was still hard going. In those days things were easier to come by. You could still find people on the roads. You'd find people fleeing their towns, towing their keepsakes, usually sick with fear and desperate to find somewhere safe. Sometimes they were already injured. Easy pickings.    They'd come in little groups, sometimes families. Never much of a threat. But the old man was different: he was alone. Just pulling a little wagon of books and some lab stuff or something.    You wanna know the rest? Live another year, and I'll tell you.  -Lucky  <font size='15'>

<font face='$HandwrittenFont' size='20'>Entry #1 - Well, I made it to Jackson, and I was right! This place is perfect; plenty of materials for a shelter, good location with foundations for defenses... yeah. Teddy and I will be ok here. Time to get to work.     Entry #2 - Work continues. Slow paced, but steady enough. Haven't had any trouble yet, which both relieves and concerns me. Teddy is happy. She loves digging through all this trash.      Entry #3 - Had my first encounter with the locals. A scouting party was eyeing us up from a distance but didn't come any closer. I have a bad feeling about this, but I will try to be friendly. At first.     Entry #4 - They came to the yard and demanded "tribute". Clearly, it's an excuse to attack us if I said no. I gave them food after they threatened Teddy and stomped on her paw. They'll come back tomorrow; time to set up traps.     Entry #5 - <font face='$evaScript_Font'' size='24'>RUST KING ROOLZ

<Font size='15'>Tomorrow we move into Athens; it's been a long road but we're almost there. We're running low on food and medicine, so here's hoping there's places we can scavenge for supplies. I doubt all of those dorm rooms have been picked yet, so they could even make for a good place to settle. Maisie has been feeling sick these past few days, so we're also going to make a stop at the Super Duper Mart. Jones is from around here originally, and he seems to think he remembers there being a pharmacy inside of it. It'd be awful convenient, but I'm not getting my hopes up.

We've crunched the numbers over the last week of operation, and with the current population, the purifier can clean ~2.15 quarts of water per person. Until we can construct a second purifier, everyone is allocated no more than 2 quarts. The remaining 0.15 is being stored for population growth emergencies. DO NOT reveal this information, otherwise it will cause problems.     Please also encourage people to bathe down river on the west side of town to prevent additional contamination. We have lost too much time fishing clothes out of the filters.

Doug, we're leaving    We kept telling those students that we shouldn't bring in all those people from the factory, and now we're all catching The Rot because of it. They already dug two burn pits, but it wasn't enough. Now they're not even bothering to cart them away, but burning them in the streets instead.     We'll do much better on our own away from all these morons. They can't even give us clean water here.

Every day that goes by, I long more and more for those simple times I took for granted.   I miss good food and fresh water, sure, who doesn't. There never will be going back to those days. I'm just thankful I can still sneak up here past the military and watch the stars with you. To have you my old friend, is all I really need.

Hot and thirsty day again today. I even saw someone I knew. And she said, "Hey Cory let me in, I'm starving. I'm thirsty. I'm dying!" Tank was barking. It's just Tank and me now and nothing and nobody is getting in here unless I say so. And I never say so. When I saw her today and she said, "Please give us some water. We're dying. I know you! You've met my kids!" I fired a shot and she left. She doesn't know me. We're all dying out here. I live in the tunnel now.

FULL: To My Bestie Beatrice in Sacramento
DESC: Mail man, deliver this to my Bestie Beatrice in Sacramento Daddy owes me BIG TIME. It'd be an understatement to say this school sucks. My Aesthetic Economics prof up and vanished, my only neighborhood salon closed its doors, everyone's gone apocalypse, and worst of all, my phone line is down! Otherwise I'd be calling like a sane person. Mailing letters is for dorks and old ladies. Since classes were canceled, Chad finally had time to spend at my place, but then he strapped on his bandana, said he 'had to go help people,' and still hasn't brought back the cookie sandwich or hair care I asked for! These may be trying times, but I draw the line at off-brand dry shampoo. Yesterday some geeks shouted up at my window to come join their camp. Excuse me? This deep winter face does NOT pair with khaki. They've been setting up this huge metal thing in the river, and now they want me to DRINK the RIVER WATER? Heinous. This place is a major bummer. What gives? Miss you bestie! Kiss Coco, Wiggles, & Ruthy!
I hate being assigned patrols with the Deathclaw guys. One of these days those wild beasts are gonna turn on them and kill us all! Just wait and see.

FULL: If I can Dance with Danny
DESC: Danny doesn't love Sophie, he loves me. He just doesn't know it yet. But I do!! If I get Tommy to dance with Sophie, Danny will be wide open while Moe Zart and the Tops play this Saturday. While Sophie's busy, I can swoop in and show Danny what he's missing. Of course, someone will have to keep Valerie busy, or she'll flip her wig if she sees Tommy talking to Sophie. I think Joey and Cassie are broken up this week so I can probably use him, but I'll need to make sure they don't get back together before Saturday. So, I'll have to have Joey dance with Valerie so she doesn't see Tommy dance with Sophie and I can finally make time with Danny.

Hey Vincent,    I wanted to give you a heads up about a suspicious character that passed through here the other day. He was a sleazy, bald pig of a man named Keith Cooper. Initially he was charming, but when he saw I wasn't falling for his tricks, the mask came off. I know how gullible you can be Vin, and this asshole fancies himself quite the "opportunist".     Apparently he was in West Virginia the last few years but wasn't able to gain the ground he wanted with some group and had to fake his death. He must have heard about the way things work over here, and now believes he can climb his way to the top and build a new empire. I don't want you interacting with him and getting roped into some shit again. Honestly, I should have done the world a favor and just shot the guy.     Good news is, it sounds like West Virginia is resettling and there's pockets of good people. The Scorched Plague is still around, but less of an issue, so I'm heading out. Once I'm established, I'll come back for you and Lucy.    Stay out of trouble,  -Dan

<font face='$Typewriter_Font' size='14'>  I still can't believe it, I actually bought Griffin Mays' sidearm from Frontier Justice. The real thing. Not a replica, not a studio prop. The actual piece he used as Marshal Holt Avery.    They had it under glass like it was some ancient treasure (which, let's be honest, it basically is). I wasn't even planning on buying anything. Still deciding whether to mount it in my office or keep it tucked away. Either way, this is going in the will.

Info 2: A woman, a mother, perhaps? Or a tragic soul pretending to be one. She tried getting a hired gun down at the old bar. She was yapping at anyone in there, wanting them to clear out the chop shop to save her son. Rightly, the request fell on deaf ears, so in desperation the woman has gone and armed herself and is heading down there as we speak. We both know what's happened to her son, and what's gonna happen to her if she makes it there, and it ain't a happy ending. If you get to her first, she might be good for some quick cash, a new weapon, or, if you're feeling smart, some fresh labor.

Welcome to Dino Peaks!

Every statue on our golf course is based on real dinosaurs that once roamed the Earth, even here in Ohio! Each hole brings a different prehistoric creature to life, from gentle giants to quick-footed hunters. As you make your way around the course, you'll learn what made these ancient animals so unique, and how they once ruled North America! Dinosaurs you'll see on the course:

  • Triceratops - Three strong horns and a giant frill. A powerful defender of the herd!
  • Alamosaurus - One of the largest long-necked dinosaurs from the southern plains!
  • Appalachiosaurus - A rare predator that stalked the forests of the East!
  • Stegosaurus - Big back plates and a tail full of spikes. A walking fortress!
  • Troodon - Small, sharp-eyed, and clever. Built for speed and thinking fast!
  • Suuwassea - A more modest sauropod, named after the sound of distant thunder!
  • Brontosaurus - A gentle giant with a long neck and a peaceful nature! Dino Peaks is proud to bring the world of dinosaurs to life. We invite you to explore, play, and imagine a time when these amazing creatures roamed the Earth. Dino Peaks Managment

Please, don't throw this away.     I'm begging you, let me go. I have a son. He's sickly, and he won't last a day on his own in this heat.     I know you need workers, but I'm just a bag of bones. You need strong people, and I know exactly where you can find them.   My sister and her family? They'll be just what you're looking for. They're bulky, scary and stubborn as mules, but if you can break them, they'll be much more useful than I would ever be.     Just free me and I'll tell you exactly where they are. You have my word.

Pete,  I know I said I was just gonna rob these idiots and bail, but they're working on something that's caught my eye.  There's some old fella in charge here. Calls himself Father Lucas. Delusional nut, but people listen to him, and he's got his posse building a bridge connecting to the west. He said he'd been chosen, and that we have to 'spread the gospel' and 'expand the empire' of the Mothman.   Crazy old crank, ain't he?    Anyway, enough about that. You should come here and help with the bridge. We'll do the work, take what we can and then get the hell outta dodge together. There's a new life waiting for us in Ohio.    Come find me, won'tcha?   Sawyer.

<font face='$HandwrittenFont' size='14'>  It's been following me for days now. At first, it was a hundred yards away. Then sixty. Then twenty. I swear, I never saw it move. Not once.     It only moves when I'm not looking.    It's getting late and I need to keep the fire lit...but I can't keep my eyes open. I'm so tired.

Mom, please come with us    I know I've asked so many times, but please don't stay here. Jeanie and I are going to leave with the next scavenger group later today. Curtis said he'll tell you about this place in detail, and he insists that it's better than dying here.     Staying here drinking that dirty water is going to kill you. This new place has plenty of clean food, water, and medicine. Just think about it, please. I'll keep contact as best I can, and I'll come back to travel with you if you decide to go.     I love you,   Max

THE PROFESSOR'S LESSONS #9: ENHANCEMENT

"What fool would wager that the tortoise overtakes the hare? Would you similarly wager that the the naked cerebral cortex, the central nervous system, feeble and puny as the day it first drew breath, is as tempered, as swift, as crystal clear as the synapses blessed by the ministrations of science's neurological enhancers? Dare you deny that the labor of history's greatest minds, passed from laboratory to laboratory, can be manufactured? Injected and bottled! You shall be enhanced!" -Professor Franklin Metter, April 13, 2081, as related to Herman the Lesser upon the summit of the Cave of ASH

<font face='$HandwrittenFont' size='20'>     Martha,    It's no longer safe here, I've barricaded up the house so we can leave. But now something has spooked the horses and they've escaped. I've gone to get them back, if I'm not here by noon, leave without me.     Be careful.  Raymond

<font size='15'>Maggie,    Well, its been a whole year and you're still alive. I thought we'd lost you in Athens, but you turned up. And you didn't lose the leg, even though we all thought you would. A promise is a promise, I owe you the rest of tale. You wanted the rest of the story of that day, when we found the Professor.    Herman had one of them laser pistols he'd lifted off an officer, a real beauty, and he put it to the old man's head. Told him to hand over his books, his medicines, whatever. The way I heard it, the old man just glared at him, asked him how far he thought he'd get with it before the photonic chamber degraded and when was the last time he checked the alignment on the crystal array?    All these questions. Had he thought about optimizing the wavelength? What about his armor? How was he going to recharge the fusion cell without compromising its capacity? Would he like the answer? How many people did he aim to kill? Was it an angels-dancing-on-the-head-of-a-pin situation? I heard Herman's mouth went slack.    The old man had a proposition: "You can have these books, which you will not understand, or you can lower that weapon, come with me, and become a very important man."     That was what I heard, anyway. And we been following him, The Professor, one way or another, ever since.    -Lucky  </font>

<font size='17'><font face='$HandwrittenFont'>This place stinks. Josh got into a fight at the party the other night. Some guy bumped into him and it got worse from there... I had to help him and now everyone hates us for ruining it.    Not only that, but deadlines are coming up for our assignments and I haven't even started mine. We're done with Athens. Caitlin, Josh, and I are gonna hitch a ride on the next train outta town.     We were in the diner and overheard one of the workers talking about a train leaving from Athens at around lunchtime. We've been talking about getting out of here for a while now; it sounds like this could be our chance.     We don't really have a place in mind, and we don't really know where the train is going, so we're just gonna hop on and see where it takes us.    Josh seems to think it could lead us to Cleveland, or even Pittsburgh. Wherever we end up, I know for sure it's gonna be better than this hellhole.

<font face='$HandwrittenFont' size='20'>Well, it looks like I'll die in here.     I can't go any further. Took a wrong turn and a damn Deathclaw attacked me! I'm bleeding out but managed to crawl away and lock the door behind me. Can't feel my legs anymore.    Dani was right. I should never have tried tunneling my way out of this place. There's nothing but death in here. I can hear her voice in my head saying, "I told you so!"    Well, I hope you're happy.     And if anyone ever finds this note, please give all my belongings to Alex. I still owe her 20 caps for the shovel.     Dani, I'll be back to haunt you!  Steve

<font face='$HandwrittenFont' size='20'>I dropped one of Dusty's stupid keys between the floor grates.    Went to tell him and he just laughed at me.  "No key? No loot."    There's caps in it for you if you can get me that key!

<font face='$HandwrittenFont'>Happy anniversary, my love. I made my way down to the lake again-just like the old days, sitting on that same bench where I first laid eyes on you, where we used to watch the otters together.     It's not the same anymore. Some fancy newfangled agricultural people got involved a few years back, promising to make our lives better. Started with them dumping a little into the lake; little became a lot quickly. Can't take a dip in it anymore. There was this big lawsuit. Talk of the town for a little bit. A kid got real sick. Never did hear what came out of it; the family left not long after it started.     I suppose after the kids left we just stopped coming. I should have brought you more; you always loved it. When I'm here, it feels like I have a piece of you with me again. I think I'll keep coming. I do wish the otters were still around.

<font face='$HandwrittenFont'>I actually did it! Of course, I knew eventually I'd get it, but even I was having doubts by version 8. Wait until everyone back in Highway Town sees this! Just imagining what they'll say about me, no more calling Willow crazy or obsessive, that's for sure.     It wasn't easy, Stomper version 1 was almost it for me. I really did think playing Radscorpion mating sounds out of a speaker was a real astute plan. I should have known it would have caused them to swarm faster than than a pack of ghouls on Jet.     This'll be worth it. These damn bugs will remember the name Willow for the rest of their short lives. Now, if only I had a way to actually kill the critters... Should have considered that earlier. This might prove harder.

If you're reading this, Schmidt got us killed just as we said he would. Athens has been a legend of untouched loot for a reason, but he insisted that we'll not only be fine, but rich beyond worries.     Walking in, Deb shared my sentiment of unease, but Schmidt insisted that the warning signs were too old to be relevant. Setting up camp at the university seemed to prove him right, and by damn did he rub it in. Once set up, he had half of the group head in to scout while the rest of us rested. They've been gone a while now, and it's getting dark. We're starting to worry.     I think I hear things creeping around us, and if we're sprung, I'm not sticking around. And since you're reading this, you shouldn't either.

Murphy,  I don't know how much longer we can hold out. Sooner or later, someone is going to overpower us and force their way in. Or someone will pick the key to the armory from the bones of our post.    I'm taking the key and heading east, down the tracks. Maybe I can find some place safer than this.     The final bit of good we can do is keep those weapons sealed away. God knows, weapons have cost this world enough.   - Greer

<font face='$76HandwrittenNeat_Font'>I've lived here my whole life, but I don't recognize this place anymore. There are soldiers in the streets, marauders on the roads outside of town. And now people have their skin falling off, talking crazy and getting violent. Nobody knows why but we see it more and more. Day and night I can smell the burn pits. I don't want to stay. I'm too afraid to go. Sometimes I wish we hadn't survived the war.

<font face='$76HandwrittenNeat_Font'>Steve,    Another sleepless night in the dorm led to a revelation. The coach would call it the big play. Do you think about how much stuff there is lying around out there? That somebody could just go take it? I snuck out with some of the bleeding hearts; Delivering supplies to the people outside of town and it struck me: how weak they are. They aren't gonna make it. It's a waste of time to help them.    Now, I get it sounds wrong but hear me out. If we don't wise up and get out of here, we're going to end up just like those folks: sick, weak, and starving.    Or, we could get a few like-minded guys from the team, get out of here, and live like kings. Maybe round up the biggest guys and them on board. After all, it's not like those are our families out there.    -Rocko
Buck,  Meet me at midnight. Bring as many buckets as you can carry. We'll take as much water as we can from the river. Maybe the purifier those students built really works? Don't get caught.  Sally

<font face='$76HandwrittenNeat_Font'>Mom,    I went out with some of the college kids; we wanted to help. We took some food and water, but we ran into trouble when we got to Albany.  We ran into some people on the roads. People that had guns. We told them we were here to help, and they took everything. They shot Jerome dead.We tried to come back to town, but the soldiers wouldn't let us near. I know we weren't supposed to drink the water, but we were so thirsty. Now we're sick. Our hair is falling out. We've all got these sores too. They itch and burn. Marge is having trouble speaking and her nose is turning black. There are other sick people out here too. We're sticking together so the bandits can't take the food we can find.    I'm really scared. I'm sorry I left.    I love you,    Janet

Cliff's Journal 11/15/2077  I never trusted Abraxodyne. Even before they laid me off, I thought something was wrong. Yeah, I took a job there like most people I know, but I guess I never believed it was really safe. I don't know what happened to their facility when the bombs dropped, but their hazardous material is loose in the atmosphere. All those chemicals, all those tanks.    Their poison is everywhere. Burning my eyes and lungs. Killing Athens.

Issac,     I know things are really hard right now but we have to keep our heads. We have to apply what we've learned. It's true that when we started our studies at Hocking, we didn't expect to be doing real engineering for a long time. Well, expectations went out the window when somebody decided it was time to drop the bombs. Now we have figure out a way to make this water purifier work, or people are going to die.     I believe in you. I believe in us.    Love,  Marsha

Gloria,    My rash is spreading. I'm losing some hair too. Writing this so you won't come back to the house. They said it's not contagious but I'm not taking chances. Stay with your sister. I'm afraid to go outside. Afraid that if the soldiers find me, they'll throw me out, or lock me up, or put me in one of those burn pits like they did with the Millers when they died. I'm praying it clears up soon. Maybe you can find me some ointment.    Karl

<font face='$76HandwrittenNeat_Font'>Everyone in town heard the crash. We always lived by the tracks, but now I guess we don't live anywhere.    We were volunteering at the church after the news. About the bombs, the war. Mom said that helping others is the best way to help ourselves right now. Her hands were shaking. Other people were crying. It didn't seem real. Not back then. Now, it seems real.    Not long after we heard about the war, we heard the train. I don't know what the train was carrying when it derailed. Some kind of chemicals? They're red, and they soaked into everything.     We tried to get back to our house after and whatever spilled out of the train burned my eyes and made me cough. The soldiers came and told us we can't go back there. Maybe not ever.

<font face='$76HandwrittenNeat_Font'>June,  I saw a rat run by and my first thought was, "dinner!" My god. I'm sure it's looted clean by now, but what I wouldn't give for another visit to the Super Duper mart down the road. I'd grab a turkey dinner and as much ice cream as I could carry. I guess I never really thought about everything we had.  -Amy

Frank's been my neighbor for twenty years. When his son broke his arm, I took him to the hospital. When they cancelled his milk route, I helped him get a plant job at Abraxodyne. When I woke up last night, I found him in my house. Snuck in through the window. He was trying to take our water. When he saw me, he turned to leave. He didn't say anything, but he was crying. What is happening to us?

Jerome,    I know your heart is in the right place, wanting to sneak out and take supplies to people in the countryside. But what about us? What about the fact that we need supplies too? What makes their lives more important than ours? Why shouldn't we go out and scavenge for ourselves? Don't bother answering. I know what you'll say.    I'll be gone by the time you look for me.  Ellen

<font face='$76HandwrittenNeat_Font' size='16'>  S Sullivan's Log,   I admit, when I heard Schmidt's pitch on Athens, I was skeptical. Anyone would be. Everyone knows the stories -- the cursed city, the place of no return, etc. Seems crazy, but the man is convincing.     But he's right-its not some deathtrap. It's fearsome reputation is just a bunch of tall tales. The city is abandoned.     We've been here for hours, and we haven't seen so much as a single ghoul. We'll be out here by tomorrow night with as much haul as the brahmin can carry. The only problem I got is how I'm going to spend all the caps from this run.

<font face='$Typewriter_Font' size='16'>Dean Wilson,    Respectfully, I disagree with your speech. Captain Murphy has no right to tell us that we can't leave, can't aid our neighbors. They're right down the road, not in a foreign country. They're American too. For god's sake there are children out there. If we don't rise to the occasion and have the courage to face this crisis, together, how can we hope to survive? The only thing that matters is people, and, right now, people have got to help each other.    I'm going out tonight, and a few other students and townspeople are coming with me. We're bringing anyone who can travel back. If they're too sick or hurt to travel, we can take supplies to them. I understand that you've got to do what you think is right but I hope you won't report us.     - Jerome Simms, Hocking Hills University Class of 2078 President

<font face='$76HandwrittenNeat_Font'>June,    We need to get out of here. Something that walked like a man, but couldn't be, came into Athens today. It ran through the square, past the festival. It was screaming, flailing. The flesh was falling off and it had no hair. From its clothes, it looked like it used to be a mailman. It still had a satchel and there were letters in it. The thing looked dead.    I was there when the soldiers shot it down. They shot it over and over and it kept running. Running and screaming until it was on the ground shot. It was looking right at me, and it seemed to be mouthing the word "help" over and over. After, they went to fetch their doctor. They told me not to panic and to go home, right away. Did that used to be a person? Can it happen to us?    We need to leave, tonight.    -Amy

Jake,    I think they know I'm watching. I count them until night falls and I can't see. Last week I counted around thirty. Tonight it was at least sixty. Murphy hasn't authorized us to fire. Not yet. So hold your fire for now. Just count how many you see.     -Vanderman

Plan: Highway Town Chems Store Sign

DESC: Bill, Here's the list for this week's run. Tommy said he'll take you along the north eastern route - claims he saw a bunch of those Radhogs up there. Make sure he doesn't take you astray from the path; he can't help but try to explore. Some of the ingredients I need require a radstorm to be happening but, trust me, my concoctions will be worth the danger! - 15 x Radhogs - 6 x Glowing meat - 5 x Red Hot Blooms - 10 x Blast Caps - 8 x Aster - 15 x Prickeye Plants (the new recipes are a hit!) - 7 x Firecaps - 6 x Brain fungus - 20 x Water You and Tommy can have first dibs on my next culinary masterpiece as a token of my appreciation. - May P.S. Remember to grab one of those hazmat suits for your travels. Those radstorms are vicious. Oh, and be careful with those prickeyes... they're called that for a reason.

Dan, What's the hold up? Where have you gone? You said you knew someone who could show us how an increased concentration of radiation affects those Radhogs. You know we need to finish my dad's research on these creatures. This was the only thing that brought him joy after the bombs dropped. We know that they seem to hang around that prickly plant we found too. I'm certain there were some out by that checkpoint tower. We may as well see the effects on these while we're there too. Remember, if you want your name on the findings, you really need to pull your weight. I can't keep doing the bulk of the work for only half the credit. - Niamh

Lou, Your cloud watching up top ain't "meteorology". We used to have machines for that, and the kinda math I couldn't explain in a lifetime. What are you gonna tell me, "a rad storm is about to hit the North so don't go there"? I wasn't going to anyway, there's Deathclaws in the North! Who cares if they're glowing? All you're gonna do is overstress the scaffolding, and one day I'll be real heartbroken when I find a Lou-shaped pancake down on the riverbed. You're a good kid, and I won't have you die on me from misplaced enthusiasm. If I catch you climbing again, you're on manure stockpiling duty for three weeks. Pop
I can see town through the trees, it's so close. But after seeing what they did to others who were sick, there's no way they'd let me in     Why is this happening?     I just want to go home

I told him to lay off...    Boss never listened to anything but his gut.     Now we've got these two fools bickering over who should lead us.    Honestly, I'm more scared about what the Rust King's gonna do when he finds out the boss ain't around no more.    Maybe we just don't tell him.    Hold up in camp and figure it out.    As long as people keep passing by, we can survive on the pie.     But we need to tinker with this recipe as soon as possible. We can't have more people turning out like the boss.

<font face='$Typewriter_Font' size='14'>October 2096,    The gangs are changing. They come in groups, not strays. I heard them whisper about the Rust King, a warlord pulling every cutthroat into his fold. They painted his mark on the lot before they left. After they were gone, Clara fetched a brush and paint and covered it. She said she would never let their colors stain this place. Brave, but I could see her hands trembling.

<font face='$Typewriter_Font' size='14'>April 2102,    They returned and this time they demanded tribute to the Rust King. Meat, caps, whatever we had. Pay, they said, or be shot. We gave them what they wanted.     None of us liked it, but it kept us alive. Dorothy still wears her spacesuit from Echoes from Nowhere. She says it feels right, like she is holding on to what we were. But her hands shake when she pulls the helmet on.

<font face='$Typewriter_Font' size='14'>August 2105,    We had food and water stored inside the old screen. Enough to last years if we were careful. Last month we found something else hidden away, a stash of weapons sealed in rust and oil. We thought maybe it was time. That maybe we could stand up to them when they came again.    We never got the chance. The Rust King's warband came in force. Dozens of them, armed for slaughter. They did not speak this time. They opened fire and cut everyone down where they stood in their costumes.    I found Dorothy in the staff room. She had not even risen from her chair. A bullet through the chest. Still in her suit. Still trying to keep the place together, even at the end.    The Rust King took everything from me. Now I will take everything from him. His raiders will see me in the dark, they'll remember the haunted clown of the Starlight. And they'll know fear again.    -- Valdimir

<font face='$Typewriter_Font' size='14'>June 2090,    Raiders came instead of scavengers . Better armed. Less frightened. They laughed at us, called us fools in children's clothes. Ruth tried to hold the snack bar. They shot her down without a thought. We buried her behind the screen still in her costume. Sadly there are fewer of us now.

<font face='$Typewriter_Font' size='14'>November 2077,    The bombs fell, but Dorothy and I stayed. So did a handful of the others. The world outside was in ruins, but here the screen still stood, the booths still stood. We pulled on the costumes, all of us. Ghosts of the Starlight. People came wandering, saw the masks, and ran screaming. We didn't have to fight. Not yet.

<font face='$Typewriter_Font' size='14'>March 2083,    The trick still works, most of the time. Travelers whisper about the "haunted drive-in." They keep their distance. But scavengers are getting bolder. A few threw rocks before running. One shot at the screen. Dorothy said the masks wouldn't protect us forever.

<font face='$Typewriter_Font' size='14'>September 2105,    The camp is looking better every night. Raiders wander too close, and I catch them. They scream, they beg, but the mask keeps me laughing. When they are quiet, I take what I want.    The bodies make good guests. I set them up in a circle, each with a hat or a mask, rifles propped across their laps. I give them bottles to hold, cards to play. A proper party. When the firelight hits their eyes, it almost looks like they are smiling back at me.    Whispers on the road of a haunted clown of the Starlight. The painted ghost that hunts in them shadows. That is what they call me now, and I think it fits just fine.    -- Vladimir the Clown

The plan is for half of us to hunt for some food for the night while the rest will look around see what we can gather from this place. Later, once we've eaten, we're going to try and find a way in to clear whatever it is inside. Then it's time to finally start building a home. Hopefully this is our last "permanent" base for a long time.

<font face='$HandwrittenFont' size='16'>Callum,    You asked me a few days ago what it was like before the Rust King's Offer and how I received it. I'm guessing this is for your little history side "project". I don't normally do things like this but you beat me at the shooting range fair and square.     The first few years were tough but nothing I couldn't handle. I ran with a group of people from my university back in Athens, ex-footballers, big guys. We learned quickly that it was a kill or be killed world and we all had to adapt. This one guy, Steve, used to be real timid but with the new world lifestyle and a little psycho, he became a monster in a fight. Back then we thought we lived like kings, taking what we wanted and killing anyone or anything that would fight back.     Eventually, reality caught up with us. Food and medicine became scarce and radiation took its effect on people. We took refuge in an old substation and on that night we met him. We'd only heard rumours, how some other groups had banded together under the rule of one guy.    Steve woke me up saying we were surrounded. They called themselves the "Rust King's Army" and claimed we were trespassing on their land. Before any of us could say anything, the shooting started. The fight was brief, only Steve, myself and one other guy (I can't remember his name) survived. We were on our knees and that was when we saw him. A goliath of a man walking through his men. The other guy started pleading for his life. The Rust King grabbed this guy's skull with both hands and just squeezed til his head burst. Steve started spewing all kinds of insults, out of fear or anger I don't know, but all the Rust King did was laugh. He took a knife from one of his raiders, "The strong live, the weak die. Which one are you?", then threw it between the two of us.     I don't remember much after that, it's all just a blur but I do remember the end result. I was bloodied and beaten but alive. When I looked down, all I saw was a bloodied rock embedded in what was left of Steve's head. At some point, the knife was disarmed so instinct must have taken over. I grabbed whatever I could and just started to pummel. The offer was made to me one last time, so I accepted. I realised then that the life I was living before wasn't that of a king, it was of a rat. Whatever sense of power we had before wasn't even a fraction compared to the Rust King. Real kings command power, strength over the weak, and I wanted to be part of it.    Don't ask me to do this again.  Rocko

<font size='20'>We came upon a church on a hill.    I told him I had once spoken in a place very similar to this.    He told me this place was a source of life.    I agreed with him.    He said that the people who flocked here served as easy prey.    Easy prey for the young among his army to learn from.    I said no more.    We continued to the north.     I pray and reflect on Matthew 21:13.
Psalm 51. May the Lord have mercy on my soul.

<font size='20'>I had not set more than a foot in this land before they found me.    I was relieved that they riddled me with questions and not bullets.    I told them I traveled to spread the word of the Lord.    They laughed. There is only one lord here, they said.    They took me to him. Their King.    I pray and reflect on Acts 9:15.

<font size='20'>On reaching Athens, I told him I could see no more.    He took me to a rooftop and told me we had reached the end.    He pointed me to the north. Commanded me to spread his scripture far and wide.    I asked him if this was a warning to the world.     He told me it was an invitation.    To the strong and like-minded.    To come to his land. To thrive and grow strong.    To challenge him and die by his hands.    I refused. I'd rather cut out my own tongue than lead others here.    He said the look in my eyes would send the message all the same.    He departed.    I sat upon the rooftop for some time. I hoped his men would return.     To kill me for my defiance.    They never came.     I pray and think upon Matthew 4:8.

<font size='20'>They placed me before his throne. Spiked, and twisted. A crown of rusted metal upon his head.     He asked me if my job was to tell stories about my Lord.     I told him they were not just stories, but scripture.     I said they are accounts of the divine reaching out to humanity.     Events that teach us lessons to live as righteous people in service to the Lord.    This answer seemed to please him.    I pray and reflect on John 18:33.

We encountered a Deathclaw.    He killed the brute swiftly, effortlessly.    He told me that he found kinship in the creatures.    They were hunters like him.    He had his men raise them from eggs for the arena.    I asked him if he saw the Deathclaws as his children.    He said this kingdom was his child. His seed, the blood spilled on its soil.    I did not prod further on this subject.    He said this story reminded him of something he wanted to show me.    We continued further down the road.    I pray and reflect on Genesis 9:2.

<font size='20'>We reached Highway Town.    The King once tore through this place with fury.    After, they would rebuild, but weaker than before.    Eventually he stopped, and let them grow.    I asked if this was mercy.    He told me that dung is needed to attract flies.    Life would need to grow if he wished to face a worthy challenge.    I asked him if the people here were insects or challengers.    He said that is for them to decide.    I pray and reflect on Judges 2:21.

<font size='20'>We walked among the red hills of his land.    I asked him why he allowed me to live.    He wanted scripture made in his name.    I explained that it isn't so simple as that.    He said I would understand after seeing his kingdom.    We left for a settlement to the north.    I pray and reflect on Ezekiel 28:2.

<font size='20'>We came upon piles of bones.    He said this place held special meaning to his army.    He once invited Highway Town to accompany their children here.    He was to recruit the strongest among them.    Scores of parents and children arrived.    They were given a blade and a choice.    The last of them standing would join his army.    Some gave themselves to their children's blades. Others, the opposite.    Some refused. They became his army's first prey.    I gagged and retched at this tale.    I begged him to tell me this was a story, a tall tale to spread fear.    He told me it is not a story. It is scripture.    We made for Athens.    I pray, and pray.     I reflect on Leviticus 18:21... On Kings 3:27... Ezekiel 16:20... Matthew 18:10...

<font size='20'>I retraced our steps.    I visited each location he showed me and meditated on their meaning.    When raiders found me, they would let me pass.    They told me I had a mission. To leave and spread his scripture.     Instead, I left my writings behind.    A show of my own might.    Then his words on the rooftop rang in my head.    These writings weren't his scripture.    I was.    I reflect on Corinthians 3:2.

One of the captives made a run for the bridge. Shame Baines put a bullet in the back of her head before she made it. Wanted to draw out the other cultist freaks and have a good, clean hunt: my patrol has been lookin' lean and hungry lately. The excitement might give 'em a kick up the ass, too. Some are getting lazy.  Nothing to worry about though, boss. I'll beat 'em into shape.

<font face='$HandwrittenFont' size='20'>You've been told before! Handlers only get their gear once they survive the trials! Quit crying and just be glad you're still alive right now. Most people don't make it this far.    - Beastmaster Lina

<font face='$HandwrittenFont' size='20'>I'm the one who went out and proved themselves! NOT YOU! I'm the one that will become a Handler! ME! If I EVER find you near MY EGG again, I will gut you like a rat and feed your insides to MY Deathclaw.    Sara

<font face='$HandwrittenFont' size='20'>The Deathclaws inside are currently undergoing starvation training.      If I find out any of you are messing with them, I'll make sure that the offenders will become their first meal.    -  Beastmaster Lina

<font face='$HandwrittenFont' size='20'>If you see any white briefcases with that Abraxo symbol on it, I'm collecting them.    I can't open them yet but I will. The contents are mine!    If you steal from me, I'll chop off your hands and shove 'em somewhere unpleasant!    -- Danny

<font face='$HandwrittenFont' size='20'>I don't care if you hear scratching, crying, or your mommy screaming for help!    Your job is to make sure that door stays sealed shut!    You got that?!     KEEP. IT. SHUT.

invutashun! treshur hunting party at the cherch

bring yur own shuvvel

<font size='20'>To any surviving Hog-heads reading this...    I have braved the ruins of Columbus and the wastes between to bring you great news:  The Horseshoe is no more-- just a smoldering crater in the ground!    Sure, we've been eliminated from playoff contention in Week 1 for the past 15 years,  but whose stadium is still standing, huh!?    Go Hogs!

Milly, How I've yearned for the verdant camaraderie of a fellow botanical soul. Your absence brings a drought upon my dreary days. I have a tale to share with you, though, my dear sister. Recently, I was recruited by my fellow survivors to discern edible flora from the fallout. Not long after, I encountered a most peculiar prickly specimen--spiny, bulbous, and seemingly fruit-bearing. Expecting a cactus pear, I cleaved it open... only to be met by an eye staring back at me... That's right, dear sister, a buckeye! In my zeal, I impaled my thumb upon its thorny husk and, through gritted teeth, declared, "This is no buckeye, it's a prickeye!" My companions erupted in mirth. They still laugh, even as I write to you. I remain perplexed that childish wordplay around the prickly nature of the specimen would prove so humorous to them. Ha! The working class, so charmingly simple! Even still, to help warn others of its prickly and puncturous nature, I shall deem this find "the Prickeye." What a refreshingly apt and unassuming name, I'm sure you agree. I shall dispatch this missive to you posthaste, dear Milly. I hope the summer home has fared better than we have. Bartholemew

Ecological Brief: Fire Beetle Migration to Eastern Ohio

Abstract: Field research confirms an abnormally high population increase of fire chaser beetles in the eastern parts of Ohio. Higher concentrations have been found in areas affected by the wildfires of the 2050's. Findings: Population growth far exceeds the bounds of native breeding cycles. Migration from across the continent is likely based on physical variability found within specimens. Discussion: The speculated range that the beetles have traveled supports emerging evidence of their heat detection mechanisms being influenced by infrared radiation from the fires and not smoke. Conclusion: The rapid increase in population could pose a threat to local agriculture. Chemical intervention is recommended. Post-Script: We've had at least one instance where a large gathering of cigarette smokers has led to swarming beetles. See: last year's Hogs Thanksgiving Game. Go Hogs!

Status report:

Abraxodyne is cornering us out of the market. Whether it's prime real-estate or some dinky field, they are outbidding us every step of the way. Surveys of the 2050's fire sites came back as expected. Widespread burning springs, likely connected to a massive natural gas reservoir. Their frequency over the years only increases the potential value in this land. None of that matters if we can't get firm footing here. Big Meadows was a failure, and the Harper's Ferry site would need decades of work to reach anywhere close to here. Running out of options. That said, I cannot in good conscience recommend that crackpot Lewisburg plan. I've no reason to believe the reservoir extends that far out. There's a good chance we've gotten false information on how lucrative that site could be.

NOTE: Intercepted by our man at Bysshe. Let's keep the pressure on.

Bleeding out. Need to write fast. Vinny wanted us to scope out the western routes. We trudged to the banks of the Ohio, found a road, followed it to a giant gate. Took maybe five seconds inside before they opened fire. Cut us off from the back, forced us further into this hellhole. Only Denny was far enough behind to turn tail back to Appalachia. Those psychopaths kept the chase on us. Picked us off one by one. Last one left. Hope Denny made it. Better get word to Vinny: stay the f

Windy, If you're reading this, you're too late. We've had to pack up shop. Can't get into details, really, but we were left with little choice. I'm headed back to HQ with the folks we had here-- yeah, even him. Sorry we couldn't wait for you to join us, but you know the route and you're always welcome to catch up. That said, I'm a bit worried about that last letter you sent. I know you're the adventure-seeking type, but from what I've heard about that wasteland, you're lucky to make it ten feet in before dying a terrible death. Please reconsider, Marley

This is a proof of transaction between Splint of Highway Town and Windy Park. Ms. Park acknowledges that I will reproduce and sell the schematics as I see fit. Welcome to Highway Town, Windy.
